commit_message:
Invalid JSON in dynamic registration of minion

The JSON was invalid as passed via curl to dynamically register
minions.  This results in the magnum minions not being dynamically
registered.

Co-Authored-By: Andrew Melton <andrew.melton@rackspace.com>

Change-Id: Ia7fbaf10e36775ff77107afe5c384a0300b78348
Closes-bug: #1448313
Partially-Implements: blueprint python-k8sclient

commit_message:
Fix bay_create_timeout not specify issue

Currently, if we didn't specify the bay_create_timeout in bay create
request, the bay create rpc call would be failed.

This patch set the field to 0 if bay_create_timeout is not specified
in the post request.

Change-Id: I7582050a5c3727053fec3a80a24098a73b2b5db8
Closes-Bug: #1448335

commit_message:
Test for shutting down eventlet server on signal

There was no test that verified that when an eventlet-based server
was sent a SIGTERM or SIGINT that it would shut down even if there
was a connected client.

Change-Id: I5e1d008bcf5413307a651620d267836ac493070d
Related-Bug: 1446583

commit_message:
Exit the poll loop when bay update failed

Currently, poll loop can exit when bay create or delete failed,
the loop should also exit when bay update failed.

Change-Id: I1b1ca37845ed517f096619ca8219b8a2f3efac13
Closes-Bug: #1448854

commit_message:
Fix sqlalchemy try...catch problem

As suggested by oslo.db, the behavior of doing try...catch in sqlalchemy
apis is no good. It will causes some problems in addition to being not
necessary.

Change-Id: I6f2be88cdb0315ae51f678251759d5966a162003

commit_message:
Move federated auth plugins to separate repo.

This patch aims to prepare keystoneclient for use of repositories
implementing various federation auth plugins. That said, keystoneclient
should only implement a common interface for them.

Work items:

*) Implements basic interface for subsequent federation auth plugins
*) Removes implementation of existing SAML2 auth plugins

Change-Id: I9f208844eb854d503b9b103cd4ede589ce13877e
Partially-Implements: bp refactor-federated-plugins

commit_message:
Make datetime output in ISO format

The default UTC datetime is precise but not needed. It needs more screen
asset for output. We adopt the common practice to output datetime in ISO
format with this patch.

Change-Id: I1a15816e006b163ca6b412c8ac36431e9f35d847

commit_message:
Fix for the deletion of an error share server

Check if share server name is in the parameter server_details when tear down
the share server. If not, just simply return.

Change-Id: Iff85589e198c933b0af67e288ed688be6e1deb39

I'm not sure, what is the best practice to add a new job to project. Do you think, that we should merge patch to Ironic at first or we can add this job now?"}, {'account_id': 10035, 'date': '2015-02-19 22:03:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

Yes, looks like ironic doesnt work with 3.4 at the moment. Non voting for now seems reasonable.'}, {'account_id': 6316, 'date': '2015-02-20 19:11:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

The workflow I like to see when adding a new job is add the job to the experimental pipeline and then flesh out the job so it can at least build. Then once the job can build move it to non-voting in check so that failures can be tracked and bugs in the tests fixed. Once the job can run in a stable fashion, passing when it should and failing when it should, then it should be moved to voting in check and gate.

I can't speak for what other reviewers like to see in a new job workflow."}, {'account_id': 5805, 'date': '2015-02-20 23:21:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Documentation for over subscription

Over subscription in thin provisioning was added in Cinder in Kilo.
This patch added documentation for it.

Change-Id: Idbe0602f306a6c21d5544a5af1ffda646f5aa813

commit_message:
Use function calls for user operations

This is due to the fact that openstack sdk recommends using function
call interface rather than the resource interface.

Change-Id: Ic7cb6ba77c28793d7c0159b6e0676888f25c89fc

commit_message:
Set node status to DELETED after node deletion

This patch invokes update_and_save rather than soft_delete in
db_api.node_delete to ensure node status will be set to DELETED
after node deletion succeeded.

Change-Id: I92d69a6aff498901f466b77d8e8de72b7d1362b7
Closes-Bug: #1448855

commit_message:
Use python from venv for subunit-trace

When running test on the environment with requirements installed
from packages, command subunit-trace might fail to import module
subunit.

This is becase subunit-trace installed from python-tempest-lib
package, and goes to /usr/bin/subunit-trace, while subunit
module is installed by pip into venv. Thus, if subunit-trace
is called as binary, is will use system python and fail to
import module from venv.

To avoid this, let's call subunit-trace as script. In that
case when running from venv we will use python from venv
and subunit-trace will find required module without issues.

Change-Id: Iaea9d8c861fdff8d5df4a59bfdf994e8f98ab3f9

Instead of heartbeating on a collection that may
be changing size while iterating ensure that we only
iterate over a copy (that won't change size) during
iteration.

The python set() docs say that it is inherently
unpredictable to iterate on a set while its being mutated

"}]
commit_message:
Heartbeat on acquired locks copy

Instead of heartbeating on a collection that may
be changing size while iterating ensure that we only
iterate over a copy (that won't change size) during
iteration.

The python set() docs say that it is inherently
unpredictable to iterate on a set while its being mutated
so we should try to avoid that kind of case if we can.

Change-Id: I6f103a5528b3f62f1c8d9e501e8cadff4221ee40

commit_message:
Remove version constraints for oslo.db dependency

ForeignKey Exception in oslo.db was printed in stderr, creating
a wrong alarming situation.

This as been fixed in oslo.db 1.8.0

Change-Id: I3c45adbde6c7445be4cbb765af07e6ad55f1afe3
Closes-Bug: #1439358

Currently, live migrations of instances with attached volumes that live
on a NetApp E-Series backend will fail and break connectivity to the

commit_message:
NetApp E-Series: Fix instance live-migration with attached volumes

Currently, live migrations of instances with attached volumes that live
on a NetApp E-Series backend will fail and break connectivity to the
guest. This patch adds the 'netapp_enable_multiattach' configuration
option that enables multiattach operations with the E-Series driver.
It defaults to allowing these operations but needs to be configurable
since allowing for multiple attachments imposes a limit of 256 volumes
on the backend due to how multiple attachments must be managed by
E-Series.

Multiattach operations are enabled by mapping volumes to an E-Series
host group on the backend called 'cinder-host-group'. Host groups can
only have 256 mappings at a time and so we must limit the number of
volumes in order to guarantee any volume created could then be attached.

Closes-bug: 1433825
Change-Id: Icb73f5b65b12decbd7b7f21c2fcec6fe700eaf59

commit_message:
ubuntu: kernel 3.13 lts for Fuel 5.1.2

Use the in-tree openvswitch datapath module if the kernel is new enough
(Ubuntu only, the out-of-tree module is unconditionally used on CentOS).

Change-Id: I9b912a6197ceb2d9566696c758282620ebbb5dc5

commit_message:
Allow pyngus to skip global requirements check

pyngus was added to help with QPID AMQP 1.0 Proton effort:
Ib8dea59922844e87d6c947b5dca557f5b5fc1160

The following change added the g-r check for pyngus:
I8fd0ef2bfc544ca2576fab09d3018f760b8848fe

However, since pyngus is not in g-r at least one job
gate-oslo.messaging-dsvm-functional-amqp1-f21 (a voting job)
is failing (used for gate/check in oslo.messaging)

Change-Id: Id7e4828056b926bf3be929f7ab104641d3031bec

commit_message:
Move optional driver requirements to test-requirements.txt

Instead of having redis, mysql, ipc, zookeeper, memcache in
requirements.txt (which are only needed if those drivers are used) be
always required move them to test-requirements.txt and require users
to install the correct requirement for there expected usage.

This leaves zake as a requirement, as that driver is the examples
default and is an in-memory driver that should/could be the default
when no other driver is accessible...

Change-Id: I410864646bb2fa401e5c827dda9bd70c6c225c74

commit_message:
Enabling Swift client retries

* set number of retries before failure to 20 by default
* enabling retries on ratelimit

partially implements bp clients-calls-retry

Change-Id: I54e57a118eca7f3e2741736d352fc96fb6669889

commit_message:
Add support for enabling/disabling service extensions

In some cases it is important to let tempest know exactly which
extensions are enabled for services such as compute and network.

This patch allows for doing it by specifiyng extension to enable
or disable in features.yaml
The test-matrix.py script has been enhanced in order to parse
information about extensions from features.yaml.
devstack-gate.sh will read these value and provide the appropriate
variable for configuring tempest accordingly in localrc.

To this aim 2 mutually exclusive options have been added to
test-matrix:
--extensions, specifying for which services enabled/disabled
extensions should be parsed
--no-extensions, to skip extension parsing.

This patch also adjusts test-features.sh to reflect the changes
in test-matrix.py and introduces test-extensions.sh to validate
extensions parsing.

Partially-implements: Blueprint branchless-tempest-extensions
Change-Id: Icddb43375f12bc7fe344074dc596f0182d67a32b

commit_message:
Fix unit issue of CONF.libvirt.live_migration_bandwidth

The wrong unit(Mbps) is used in the option description
of CONF.libvirt.live_migration_bandwidth, it mislead the
users, corrected it to MiB/s.

And add more details about this option, include: the
behavior when live_migration_bandwidth=0, and when the
hypervisors don't support it if bandwidth is not 0.

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1448844

Change-Id: I032440dc5e743c77595ae653ba859183fa38097b

``token``.

commit_message:
rabbit: more precise iterconsume timeout

The iterconsume always set the timeout of kombu to 1 second
even the requested timeout more precise or < 1 second.

This change fixes that.

Related bug: #1400268
Related bug: #1399257

(cherry picked from commit 023b7f44e2ccd77a7e9ee9ee78431a4646c88f13)
(cherry picked from commit 44132d4344902f98007e6e58ea3bee56c701b400)

Note: _poll_connection could fall into a loop waiting for a reply message, if rabbit dies and up.
This commit will set up a rpc_response_timeout timer for one connection polling; so the rpc will
finally jump out with a timeout exception which is expected in such scenario.

Related bug: #1338732

Change-Id: I898a236a384b3466147026abc7a1ee21801e8ca1

commit_message:
Merge server response schema into one file

After removing v3 schemas, we have only 1 set of schemas for v2 (/v2.1)
APIs but those end up in scattered structure.

Schema files needs to be re arranged into a clean structure. Any
resource schema should be defined in single file for better readability.

This patch merge server response schema into one file and in more
readable form.

Partially implements blueprint rearrange-nova-response-schemas

Change-Id: I028558d03c8633fd3b77e04f28a025f654bc7505

commit_message:
Switch from using custom urlparse import logic to six

This commit removes the try except logic in auth.py to import urlparse
on either python2 or python3 to use six instead. Six already provides
an interface to use urlparse the same way on either python2 or python3
which is a bit cleaner.

Change-Id: I964586af4b2df63ae81b09ac1c3f1397b0250b80

When a subunit stream for a testcase doesn't contain start end enddate,
the duration can't be calculated which leads to a:

ValueError: could not convert string to float

Check now if the duration is an empty string and add basic test coverage
based on ddt for the subunit_trace command.

Change-Id: I6fdc8d283e67becbecf58b7779e33271db048a73
"}]
commit_message:
Fix ValueError in subunit_trace

When a subunit stream for a testcase doesn't contain start end enddate,
the duration can't be calculated which leads to a:

ValueError: could not convert string to float

Check now if the duration is an empty string and add basic test coverage
based on ddt for the subunit_trace command.

Change-Id: I6fdc8d283e67becbecf58b7779e33271db048a73

commit_message:
Fix the wrong input package of pbr of cloudkittyclient

The cloudkittyclient cannot work because wrong package name was
inputed to pbr.version.VersionInfo() method.

Change-Id: Iff65bf5b2efd50b0dd29070b89ac5a607d0ecfcb
Closes-Bug: #1448406

commit_message:
3PAR don't log version numbers every stats update

After the 3PAR drivers were refactored to remove the local
file locks, the login mechanism was logging the common and
client version numbers on every driver entry point.

This patch removes that logging except at driver startup.

Change-Id: Ib7732817a45cbdfdf975df13dbaf9bc0462a1dc0
Closes-Bug: #1447697

commit_message:
Fix instance_dd_tests.sh always reading 1MiB

The dummy test script `instance_dd_test.sh' used for
`boot_runcommand_delete' reads only 1MiB disregarding thus reporting
wrong read performance.

Change-Id: I37f2913d6b525e7d65396e5db96a233987cc6679
Closes-Bug: #1448300

If you need this quickly we might go ahead with this and then integrate it in the bp implementation."}, {'account_id': 15777, 'date': '2015-03-27 15:17:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thanks a lot Koderer & Frittoli.
I've looked through BP ssh-auth-strategy in https://blueprints.launchpad.net/tempest/+spec/ssh-auth-strategy. Yes you are right, this BP is a higher level than this bug described. It provided password injected feature rather than a fixed username/password of the image.

Fortunately the changes are not conflicting. And the fixing of this bug just provide simple quick go through for SSH testing with configured password for images such as cirros. Forgive me that I haven't noticed that BP and will that include the testing like cirros image? Thanks again."}, {'account_id': 7872, 'date': '2015-03-30 06:22:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Andrea: IMHO we should merge it. I doesn't hurt and I would use it right away."}, {'account_id': 10016, 'date': '2015-03-30 08:45:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 1839, 'date': '2015-03-30 12:34:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 1921, 'date': '2015-03-30 21:47:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(3 comments)

I agree this does not conflict with the ssh-auth-bp, so I'm ok with merging this, but first I would like to see the code running if possible.
Does the cirros image in used in the gate have a configured default password? If so could you put a test change on top of this one with the correct configurations in, so we can see this running?"}, {'account_id': 15777, 'date': '2015-03-31 01:39:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Yes you are right Frittoli. Current username/password configuration is inconsistent for scenario test cases. Different cases in scenario suites may use different configs . I've put that in TODO list in the commit comment.

And yes the code doesn't change the behavior of ssh_connect_method. That's an example if we want to test SSH with floating IP. Below is the key parameter for the code change.

[compute]
image_ssh_user = cirros
image_ssh_password = cubswin:)
ssh_auth_method = configured  #default is keypair


[scenario]
ssh_user = cirros

Cirrus image that is used for testing has a pre-configured password 'cubswin:)'. And the reason why there are two username parameters is the same as what you described - current inconsistency of configuration, some of scenario cases use scenario.ssh_user but some of them use compute.image_ssh_user. Here we set both of them is for running all of the scenario SSH test cases with image like cirros, and we are glad that it will be fixed in ssh-auth-strategy bp. Thanks."}, {'account_id': 15777, 'date': '2015-03-31 06:24:59.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 15777, 'date': '2015-03-31 06:28:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Simplify commit and code comment as koderer & Frittoli suggested.
And change the test configuration example in commit comment.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-03-31 08:01:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-03-27 07:20:19.000000000', 'message': "Allow SSH instance with username and password in scenario cases

Current scenario test cases only allow SSH with keypair.
The option ssh_auth_method in conf file has never been used for
choosing SSH method. Tempest use paramiko.client.connect to login
instance and which accepts both password and keypair. It attemps to
use pkey, SSH agent key and keys in .ssh to connect and the last is
username/password. So here we change the entrance where call it:
scenario.manager.get_remote_client(). Check the ssh_auth_method to
decide which way should be picked, pass a None private to paramiko
if username/password has been chosen and vice versa.

Since disable ssh_auth_method makes most of the scenario test cases
meaningless, here the disable flag is not checked and the SSH method
is either username/password or private key.

TO test the modification for username/password authentication with
cirros, set tempest.conf as below and run senario test cases:

[compute]
...
ssh_connect_method = floating
image_ssh_user = cirros
image_ssh_password = cubswin:)
ssh_auth_method = configured  #default is keypair
...

[scenario]
...
ssh_user = cirros
...

TODO in the next:
SSH username and password come from different config options.
e.g. some of the scenario cases use compute.image_ssh_password and
compute.image_ssh_user, some of them use scenario.ssh_user or
input-scenario.ssh_user_regex. And the rest use all of them. It's
hard for user to configure for all the cases since they need to
modify many places for username, password etc. It's better to use the
same place to configure them.

Change-Id: I48e3689c4040b18e887284b8eec3a6537c6adb50
Closes-Bug: #1400638

commit_message:
Allow SSH instance with username and password in scenario cases

Current scenario test cases only allow SSH with keypair.
Here we change the entrance where call SSH client:
scenario.manager.get_remote_client(). Check the ssh_auth_method to
decide which way should be picked, pass a None private to paramiko
if username/password has been chosen and vice versa.

Since disable ssh_auth_method makes most of the scenario test cases
meaningless, here the disable flag is not checked and the SSH method
is either username/password or private key.

TO test the modification for username/password authentication with
cirros, set tempest.conf as below and run senario test cases:

[compute]
...
image_ssh_user = cirros
image_ssh_password = cubswin:)
ssh_auth_method = configured  #default is keypair
run_ssh = True #If want to test scenario.test_server_basic_opts
...

[scenario]
...
ssh_user = cirros
...

TODO in the next:
SSH username and password come from different config options.
e.g. some of the scenario cases use compute.image_ssh_password and
compute.image_ssh_user, some of them use scenario.ssh_user or
input-scenario.ssh_user_regex. And the rest use all of them. It's
hard for user to configure for all the cases since they need to
modify many places for username, password etc. It's better to use the
same place to configure them.

Change-Id: I48e3689c4040b18e887284b8eec3a6537c6adb50
Closes-Bug: #1400638

commit_message:
Update spec on over subscription

There are changes made to the original design in the approved
Cinder spec on over subscription in thin provisioning during
the review process of the code submission. Now the code is merged,
the spec should be updated to reflect the changes.

Change-Id: I765af2e69f8b7dedf078f35a2c0354aaf9f5c00e

commit_message:
[DOCS] docs.openstack.org/user-guide links recheck

Fuel documentation links to the legacy OpenStack User
Guides (that have recently been migrated to rst and
published in another location by the upstream doc team).

This commit fixes the two links that reference to the
docs.openstack.org user guides.

Change-Id: Ic080c3d41f4b7bb91afe9a810fb890cf99c40f3f
Closes-Bug: #1448123

[{'created': '2015-04-24 18:30:20.000000000', 'message': "Removing signing_dir directive from config

The signing_dir directive defined in barbican-api-paste.ini explicitly
stores Keystone's signing certificates in a known /tmp directory. This
could be exploited by populating the directory with bogus certificates,
potentially allowing a malicious user to generate valid tokens.

Added comment explaining signing_dir, and a reasonable
(commented) default.

Change-Id: I15fda6863e888e3881694ab47a836eee2fb578ee
Closes-Bug: #1446406
"}]
commit_message:
Removing signing_dir directive from config

The signing_dir directive defined in barbican-api-paste.ini explicitly
stores Keystone's signing certificates in a known /tmp directory. This
could be exploited by populating the directory with bogus certificates,
potentially allowing a malicious user to generate valid tokens.

Added comment explaining signing_dir, and a reasonable
(commented) default.

Change-Id: I15fda6863e888e3881694ab47a836eee2fb578ee
Closes-Bug: #1446406

When calling get_acl_dict_for_user() in the RBAC feature, the user list
may be empty.  In this case, make sure an empty list (not None) is
returned so the receiving code won't fail.

commit_message:
Fix failure with get on dict that was None

When calling get_acl_dict_for_user() in the RBAC feature, the user list
may be empty.  In this case, make sure an empty list (not None) is
returned so the receiving code won't fail.

Change-Id: I6aeb94e03aa7898823ec408807180f7eeb2d2916
Closes-bug: #1446826

commit_message:
Do not check networks on offline nodes

net_checker should not try to verify connectivity with offline nodes.
There should be two or more online nodes in order to run net_checker.
Error message is generated otherwise.
Offline nodes quantity is saved in task's message to generate
corresponding notice upon task completion.
Notice messages should not replace error messages and each other. They
are concatenated with '\n' delimiter.

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1318659
Change-Id: Ic89593bb98241ec3d708bcbfc020b3df9610f284

commit_message:
Support config neutron api_workers and rpc_workers

Like other compoment, neutron supports scaling by setting the api_workers
and rpc_workers. The patch make devstack automatic setting these two configs.

It helps to speed up tempest tests, also make sure we do not break the worker
function.

RN6.0-updates2 Nova resolved issues

1. nova-compute times out waiting for RPC reply

Add rate-limit volume copy bandwidth

implemented in Kilo. This patch adds documentation for it.

commit_message:
Allow node_get_all_by_cluster ignore deleted nodes

Currently, db_api.node_get_all_by_cluster will return all nodes belong
to a cluster including those ones that have been deleted. This will
cause incorrect calculation result of cluster size. This patch fixes
this issue.

Change-Id: Ic465ca0775fd437bb1cdfc78d29aa79d69d3f727
Closes-Bug: #1448871

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-24 15:24:24.000000000', 'message': "Eventlet green threads not released back to pool

Presently, the wsgi server allows persist connections hence even after
the response is sent to the client, it doesn't close the client socket
connection.
Because of this problem, the green thread is not released back to the pool.

In order to close the client socket connection explicitly after the
response is sent and read successfully by the client, you simply have to
set keepalive to False when you create a wsgi server.

Add a parameter to take advantage of the new(ish) eventlet socket timeout
behaviour. Allows closing idle client connections after a period of
time, eg:

$ time nc localhost 8776
real    1m0.063s

Setting 'client_socket_timeout = 0' means do not timeout.

DocImpact:
Added wsgi_keep_alive option (default=True).
Added client_socket_timeout option (default=900).

SecurityImpact

Closes-Bug: #1361360
Change-Id: I03b9c5c64f4bd8bca78dfc83199ef17d9a7ea5b7

Because of this problem, the green thread is not released back to the pool.

In order to close the client socket connection explicitly after the
response is sent and read successfully by the client, you simply have to
set keepalive to False when you create a wsgi server.

Add a parameter to take advantage of the new(ish) eventlet socket timeout
behaviour. Allows closing idle client connections after a period of
time, eg:

$ time nc localhost 8776
real    1m0.063s

Setting 'client_socket_timeout = 0' means do not timeout.

DocImpact:
Added wsgi_keep_alive option (default=True).
Added client_socket_timeout option (default=900).

SecurityImpact

Closes-Bug: #1361360

commit_message:
Eventlet green threads not released back to pool

Presently, the wsgi server allows persist connections hence even after
the response is sent to the client, it doesn't close the client socket
connection.
Because of this problem, the green thread is not released back to the pool.

In order to close the client socket connection explicitly after the
response is sent and read successfully by the client, you simply have to
set keepalive to False when you create a wsgi server.

Add a parameter to take advantage of the new(ish) eventlet socket timeout
behaviour. Allows closing idle client connections after a period of
time, eg:

$ time nc localhost 8776
real    1m0.063s

Setting 'client_socket_timeout = 0' means do not timeout.

DocImpact:
Added wsgi_keep_alive option (default=True).
Added client_socket_timeout option (default=900).

SecurityImpact

Closes-Bug: #1361360
Change-Id: I03b9c5c64f4bd8bca78dfc83199ef17d9a7ea5b7

I get them from the context.auth_token_info, then it will only expose the public endpoint. So I still think it would be a better choice to make a configuration.'}, {'account_id': 1298, 'date': '2015-04-23 14:12:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

The problem with this approach is that if you don't provide that setting in nova and cinder, the original url is returned and things still work. Their original url is based on the public endpoint. If you take the same default behavior in heat and just return the URL if no config setting is there, it'll still be based on the internal URL and things will still be broken.

Please don't make people specify the same value in two different places. I'm fine with having a user specified prefix if they wish as long as the redirect URL is based on the *public* endpoint by default."}, {'account_id': 7404, 'date': '2015-04-23 14:55:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Okay, seems this patch is solving a problem caused by request redirection. I was misguided by the commit message.'}, {'account_id': 12929, 'date': '2015-04-24 02:41:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(2 comments)

@Ken Thomas. Hello, Ken, nova, cinder and heat get the original url from req.application_url, which means the href url depends on the the url used to access the service. For example, if you use public url to access the service, then it will return public url as href url, and if you use internal url to access the service, then internal url will be returned.'}, {'account_id': 12929, 'date': '2015-04-24 03:11:07.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 12929, 'date': '2015-04-24 03:13:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

- check-tempest-dsvm-heat http://logs.openstack.org/75/174775/3/check/check-tempest-dsvm-heat/4810160/ : SUCCESS in 21m 06s'}, {'account_id': 4571, 'date': '2015-04-24 04:19:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

Before we add another config option, is there a reason why the base url can't be fetched from the keystone catalog?"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-24 04:25:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Build succeeded (check-tripleo pipeline).

- check-tripleo-ironic-overcloud-precise-nonha http://logs.openstack.org/75/174775/3/check-tripleo/check-tripleo-ironic-overcloud-precise-nonha/0b038ed/ : SUCCESS in 1h 13m 52s'}, {'account_id': 12929, 'date': '2015-04-24 06:15:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@Steve Baker Nova people add this prefix due to the bug https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/924090. So I the advice from nova rather than get the url from keystone.'}, {'account_id': 12929, 'date': '2015-04-24 06:20:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I have also consider that we can make a configuration like heat_api_link_endpoint_type(publicURL, internalURL and adminURL), but I just wanna to keep consistence with nova and cinder etc.'}, {'account_id': 1298, 'date': '2015-04-24 13:56:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I appreciate the explanation. My concern is that something else in nova may be different from what you're doing here.  

The original bug was only seen in heat. Nova worked just fine without us having to specify a value for an additional config option. If this fix *requires* that a new config setting be specified (and kept in sync with the registered endpoints), then I'm worried you're treating the symptom and not the underlying problem.  

On the other hand, if the new config option is not specified and the default behavior fixes the original problem... wonderful! The question then is why add a new option in the first place? Just to be consistent with nova?

I'm fine with any solution as long it doesn't require keeping two pieces of information in separate locations in sync.  It's not necessary for nova to work in the situation and it shouldn't be necessary here.

Thanks!"}, {'account_id': 12606, 'date': '2015-04-25 00:42:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

Note that there is a related proposed patch for a different issue when dealing with proxy servers: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/160267/.

Like I mentioned in the other review, the issue of dealing with proxy servers exists in lots of web applications. There is a set of standard headers that proxy servers insert into requests before they are forwarded to the application. With the help of these headers the application is able figure out exactly how the URLs need to be created for the user.

For information on these headers see RFC7239: https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc7239. Basically the proxy server indicates the host the user connected to in the X-Forwarded-Host, and the protocol in X-Forwarded-Proto. The make_url function can use these headers (when present) to generate URLs. This does not require additional configuration variables to be added to heat.conf.'}, {'account_id': 12929, 'date': '2015-04-27 02:23:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@ Miguel Grinberg Very nice suggestion. But I still have a question about forwarding the http-protocal. In most case, we only configure https in the proxy, if we forward the http-protocal, then will proxy use https to communicate with openstack http-server? 

If it does,  using https in the internal environment is not a good choice since https cause lots of cpu cycles then http.'}, {'account_id': 12606, 'date': '2015-04-27 02:33:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@Deliang: There are two separate headers for host and protocol. The X-Forwarded-Host header gives you the hostname the client used to connect to the proxy server, and the X-Forwarded-Proto gives you the protocol, which can be https or http. I think this is all you need to write a complete version of make_url that is proxy friendly, but please let me know if I'm missing something."}, {'account_id': 12929, 'date': '2015-04-27 02:46:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@Miguel, I only have one puzzle as following:

         HTTPS      (fowarding-proto)        ?
User ------------------> Proxy -------------------> heat-api

If we enable forwarding-proto, which mode will proxy use to communicate with heat-api, http or https?

Sorry, I'm a freshman to proxy."}, {'account_id': 12606, 'date': '2015-04-27 02:51:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

No problem. The protocol used between the proxy and the heat-api is configured in the proxy, it can be http or https. A very common setup is to have the proxy terminate the SSL, so the proxy forwards requests to heat-api as regular http.

The protocol used between proxy and heat-api does not matter though, because in all cases the X-Forwarded-Proto header will have the protocol used between the client and the proxy, which is what you need to build URLs that are returned to the client.

Let me know if you have any other questions.'}, {'account_id': 12929, 'date': '2015-04-27 03:04:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@Miguel  OK, I have got it. So nice of you and think you very much!'}, {'account_id': 12929, 'date': '2015-04-27 07:08:10.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Heat has already fix this problem if we configure haproxy properly.'}, {'account_id': 12929, 'date': '2015-04-27 07:08:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/64142/'}]

commit_message:
Add base url in links to Orchestration API

We should provide a configuration heat_api_link_prefix that
will be presented to users in links to the Orchestration API
as other OpenStack projects do.

Change-Id: I9631ba1ff2e179cf709bf56176691b87cb847390
Closes-Bug: #1414144

(1 comment)

You need to import the coloring library into the files you want to use. Also, this method will be difficult for reviewers to test the patch so I think you should think of a way by which this patch can be tested easily. One option is to push each patch set color wise. Also it is a good practice to test the patch before submitting it to catch some obvious mistakes.'}, {'account_id': 14702, 'date': '2015-04-14 20:25:19.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-14 21:19:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

This is sort of pointless because the output of these scripts are not displayed anywhere and saved as log files. If you want to merge this colorizing functionality I would recommend adding a --verbose| -v functionailty and pipe the logs out into the host side and inject colors on the fly for STDOUT and      STDERR. You can also colorize the timestamps etc. easily using regex and redirection of the output text.'}, {'account_id': 14702, 'date': '2015-04-27 06:00:28.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

[{'created': '2015-04-20 19:56:39.000000000', 'message': "Move RBD calls to a separate threads

RBD lib is a python binding for librados and doesn't
patched by eventlet. This patch moves all rados calls to
a separate python thread.

Logs from cinder-volume after patch apply:
http://paste.openstack.org/show/204915/

Change-Id: Ibaf43858d60e1320c339f2523b5c09c7f7c7f91e
Closes-Bug: bug #1401335
"}, {'created': '2015-04-20 20:10:27.000000000', 'message': "Move RBD calls to a separate threads

RBD is a python binding for librados which isn't patched by eventlet.

Making long-running tasks like removing big (~100GB, ~1TB) volumes
blocks eventlet loop and all cinder-volume service hangs
until it finished when rados_connect_timeout is disabled. It makes
cinder-volume services unavailable for a while.

This patch moves all rados calls to a separate python thread which
doesn't block eventlet loop.

Logs from cinder-volume after patch apply:
http://paste.openstack.org/show/204915/

Change-Id: Ibaf43858d60e1320c339f2523b5c09c7f7c7f91e
Closes-Bug: bug #1401335
"}, {'created': '2015-04-20 20:10:52.000000000', 'message': "Move RBD calls to a separate threads

RBD is a python binding for librados which isn't patched by eventlet.

Making long-running tasks like removing big (~100GB, ~1TB) volumes
blocks eventlet loop and all cinder-volume service hangs
until it finished when rados_connect_timeout is disabled. It makes
cinder-volume services unavailable for a while.

This patch moves all rados calls to a separate python thread which
doesn't block eventlet loop.

commit_message:
Move RBD calls to a separate threads

RBD is a python binding for librados which isn't patched by eventlet.

Making long-running tasks like removing big (~100GB, ~1TB) volumes
blocks eventlet loop and all cinder-volume service hangs
until it finished when rados_connect_timeout is disabled. It makes
cinder-volume services unavailable for a while.

This patch moves all rados calls to a separate python thread which
doesn't block eventlet loop.

Change-Id: Ibaf43858d60e1320c339f2523b5c09c7f7c7f91e
Closes-Bug: #1401335

commit_message:
Use iscsi_helper instead of target_helper on logs

With the deprecation of LVMISCSIDriver and LVMISERDriver a log warning
was introduced to request using LVMVolumeDriver and setting
target_helper, but it is missleading, as it should say iscsi_helper to
be clear on what is expected on the target configuration.

Revert "Add support for customized cluster name"

This introduces a config option, which we don't want to happen in
backports.

This reverts commit f5895fe819646f1b30b83b9d28cbaa75ff5dffc4.

commit_message:
Disable clean_step if config option is set to 0

Disabling erase_devices clean_step in agent_ilo driver doesn't work
even though the configuration option is updated to 0.

Change-Id: I72501793b9a0d384555bec2bbe2ddfdb2f1c2c2f
Closes-Bug:#1448103

commit_message:
Fixes multiple global_filter created in /etc/lvm/lvm.conf by set_lvm_filter.

This is fix for bug/1437998.
set_lvm_filter does not check if there's already any existing global_filter
and it just adds a new one which causes warnings:
WARNING: Ignoring duplicate config node: global_filter

Change-Id: I54d34237e1a1cbcad44edaf73b274b8a00ee7e99
Closes-bug: #1437998

commit_message:
Ignore multiple imports per line for six.moves

In the transition to Python3 we'll be heavily using six.move to import
builtins that have changed and modules that have moved. Having them all
on one line will, in many cases, make the code look cleaner. There is
exactly what we already do with the i18n translation helpers.

bp python3
Change-Id: I5c56a1cf36749d9f190e4360d5a12616380b6598

commit_message:
Add external genconfig calls

After moving to oslo.config we still were using
incubator config generator.  This was ok, but the
problem is we haven't been pulling config options
from the oslo libs.

This is a hack that just appends external lib calls
and appends those options to the sample file being built.

Change-Id: I2634b20ef4abd3bf7990f845d59ad3d208db234f
Closes-Bug: #1447380

(2 comments)

Sorry, while I admire the concept, I think this is better in the 'we don't support' rather than 'we're forcing it to break' camp.

In particular, buildout, conda and other packaging systems would all need to be detected, and in the absence of that we're just being mean.

So - I think the conditions for 'error' need to be:
 - independent of any particular installer
 - aware of out-of-path invocations

Now, some installers (like versions of pip prior to 6.1) don't even get the order of installation correct - pip would install things in arbitrary order. So we can't even use 'are our dependencies present' as a test to see if we're under a good installer.

tl;dr I think things are too raw in the Python packaging world to do this well yet, since 'pip install pbr-using-thing' with pip 1.5.4 (which a lot of folk have baked into their OS) is a thing we should permit to work. And special casing pip there - erg.

And don't get me started on corner cases like folk with setup_requires that pull in pbr using things so that pip can't see the deps... but that is in fact under pip - so we'd need to walk the process group to see if we're really under pip."}, {'account_id': 2, 'date': '2015-04-26 02:17:12.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-26 03:36:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

commit_message:
Loudly warn about invocation of setup.py install

easy_install makes this always something that will fail. pip install .
should be used instead.

Distro packagers still use it, but they use it with --root appended, so
allow that as a passthrough.

Change-Id: I5c5bfc2497cd75e7f60c493347a7fbcc3aa0c8e2

commit_message:
Reduce parameters to base class execute

Simplify the parameters so we are just passing a command string
to the execute command in the base class.  The string is exactly
the command we are going to run.  This will make debugging
easier and make it clearer what we are actually running.

Change-Id: I0425007e1849f31d692420e38544c55b1acb86c4

commit_message:
FirstApp section 1 updates

-Changed the words 'better' to 'higher' in
the 'What you need' section.
-Removed question marks in header text.
-Changed wording in first paragraph of
'A general overview'.
-Removed extra spaces at end of lines.

Change-Id: I74a4b3f7bee962fe56b136ccda939f2f171c50eb

commit_message:
L2gw to support VM migration

The patch set handles VM migration usecase for
L2GW. Basically, it updates Ucast_Macs_Remote
table record for the port associated with the
VM being migrated and inserts new entry in
Physical_Locators table if that locator does not
exist.

Closes-Bug:1438637

Co-Authored-By: Koteswara Rao Kelam <koteswara.kelam@hp.com>
Change-Id: Icf1a973cd3e3ac5e889c7a63405471062f1f9a0d

 HTTP/1.1 500 Internal Server Error
 {"computeFault":
   {"message": "Unexpected API Error. Please report this at

                <class 'nova.exception.SnapshotNotFound'>",
    "code": 500}}

Return 404 if run volume ops with invalid volume

Update os-volume_attachments to handle VolumeNotFound from cinder api
if invalid volume is specified during detach and update.

commit_message:
Add min/max microversions to version-list cmd

Since Id464a07d624d0e228fe0aa66a04c8e51f292ba0c, Nova returns min/max
microversions on a "list versions" API response.
For using microversions, API users need to know available microversions.
This patch adds them to version-list command.

Change-Id: I81f667ca4f0403183cac918e416a730c16b6eeff

commit_message:
Apply a naming rule of GET to compute clients(a-e)

[GET /resources] methods should be "list_<resource name>s"
or "show_<resource name>", so this patch applies the rule
to compute clients which names are "[a-e].*".

Partially implements blueprint consistent-service-method-names

Change-Id: Iaa3a295b4d7b06f7d3a7344e427eee02d0c6b96b

commit_message:
Make keystone endpoints work like the others

Consolidate the internal interface around get_endpoint and put the silly
keystone-specific logic there, rather than in keystone_client.

Change-Id: Ifc9916ccf8c8dafaff0ea27e47de0316421ac833

commit_message:
Use SHA256 instead of SHA1 for resource signature

SHA1 is not safe for signature, use sha256 instead.

Closes-Bug: #1447904
Change-Id: I093464d9c1e30d317de75a4ac3d1d51f1c110114

commit_message:
Add http:// prefix to kubelet api server

The API server was not being set to use http:// as a prefix.  This
may result in a default behavior of using https which we don't yet
support.

Co-Authored-By: Andrew Melton <andrew.melton@rackspace.com>

Change-Id: I3f4e3a6bf3ff385152d91afdb7c69f98ce71b448
Partialy-implements: blueprint python-k8sclient

commit_message:
Add etcd 2.0 config file support

Update kubernetes version to 0.15.  Kubernetes 0.15 introduces
etcd 2.0 instead of 1.y series.  The 2.0 series has a separate
configuration file in /etc/etcd/etcd.conf.  This configuration
file specifies an IP address on which to listen for ETCD requests.

Co-Authored-By: Andrew Melton <andrew.melton@rackspace.com>

Change-Id: Ifd231dd2d78ab14d7af4d013840f25630b10d469
Partially-implements: blueprint python-k8sclient

I really think cluster_type is a confusing name. Cluster_type is too generic and and be conflated with representing the distro, the coe, or even the platform. As this value is storing the operating system distro pulled from the glance image, I think a better name would be cluster_distro.'}, {'account_id': 15697, 'date': '2015-04-23 12:56:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 668, 'date': '2015-04-23 20:59:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

@apmelton: I would support changing the name to cluster_distro, as it makes sense for Linux and it's consistent with what's in Glance. 

There is another angle to consider as well. Before long, we will also have containers for Windows, and it would be nice to fit that into Magnum without too many Linux specific things to contend with.

In the case of 'Microsoft Nano Server' [1] I'm not sure what would go in the cluster_distro field. Maybe 'nano', but then there will be different versions of that. Does the suggestion still make sense after considering this?

[1] http://azure.microsoft.com/blog/2015/04/08/microsoft-unveils-new-container-technologies-for-the-next-generation-cloud/"}, {'account_id': 8580, 'date': '2015-04-24 06:16:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

@Adrian - I am replacing cluster_type with cluster_distro but I have gone through the link you have shared, "nano" is exact fit for our approach but it is used by Microsoft.

Here I am sharing some abstract about "nano server.

Nano Server, a minimal footprint installation option of Windows Server that is highly optimized for the cloud, including containers. Nano Server provides just the components you need  nothing else, meaning smaller server images, which reduces deployment times, decreases network bandwidth consumption, and improves uptime and security.'}, {'account_id': 8580, 'date': '2015-04-24 21:21:24.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 12.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-24 21:50:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12: Verified+1

Jshint unused and undef cleanup for messages JS

Removing unused and undefined variables in messages javascript.
This ensures that once we enable it globally, the gate will not barf.

Change-Id: I766951bb20c9ebb562ef35fc0fb2559fb430bd94
Partial-Bug: #1438620

messages:
[{'account_id': 9576, 'date': '2015-04-08 18:34:31.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 9576, 'date': '2015-04-08 18:34:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Commit message was updated'}, {'account_id': 9576, 'date': '2015-04-08 18:52:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Commit message was updated'}, {'account_id': 6825, 'date': '2015-04-08 18:52:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)

The 'unused' jshint option can be used to check just for unused variables AND unused function parameters ("unused = true") or to just for unused vars ("unused = vars").  I believe that removing unused variables is useful, but removing unused function parameters is questionable. Many times the unused parameters are present in callback functions which are indeed receiving those parameters, and it is arguably more correct to keep them in the function declaration.'}, {'account_id': 9576, 'date': '2015-04-08 18:52:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Commit message was updated'}, {'account_id': 9576, 'date': '2015-04-08 18:56:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

@Gary I don't think it make sense to have extra params in a callback function that you aren't using. As for function declarations, that will work as it normally does."}, {'account_id': 6825, 'date': '2015-04-08 19:03:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

There are certainly times in callbacks where you only need to used the second (or third) parameter, and this would then require extra hurdles to make jslint happy if 'unused' is set to 'true'. commit_message:
Removing unused variables in dashboard

Before we can enable a global check for unused variables, we need to clean
up the code first. This way, the gate won't barf when we try to enable the
global unused and undef jshint config.

This patch addresses the files in openstack dashboard only.

Change-Id: I4b0625ead27724ad7378ad906e2df26e00cc56ac
Partial-Bug: #1441794

commit_message:
Jshint unused and undef cleanup for forms, heattop JS

Removing unused and undefined variables in forms, formset_table,
heattop javascript. This ensures that once we enable it globally,
the gate will not barf.

Change-Id: I3d0b21dd1813fe83f28c2488cd308eee680ed690
Partial-Bug: #1438620

commit_message:
Jshint unused and undef cleanup for instances JS

Removing unused and undefined variables in instances javascript.
This ensures that once we enable it globally, the gate will not barf.

Change-Id: I2273605986b530a90f29c90a6cd52d628a6d8271
Partial-bug: #1438620

[{'created': '2014-10-07 15:03:32.000000000', 'message': 'Setting sriov service for ml2 plugin

The user should configure the following parameters in local.conf:
 - PHYSICAL_DEVICE_MAPPINGS (For Example: default:eth1)
    or
   PHYSICAL_NETWORK (For Example: default) + PHYSICAL_INTERFACE (For Example: eth1 )
- PCI_PASSTHROUGH_WHITELIST (For Example: '{"address":"*:02:00.*","physical_network":"default"}')
- Q_PLUGIN=ml2
- Q_MECHANISM_DRIVER=sriovnicswitch

For more information About SRIOV: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/SR-IOV-Passthrough-For-Networking

Change-Id: Idc502adac6cc296bf1f3256c3ca6637adccfd9c3

commit_message:
Setting sriov service for ml2 plugin

The user should configure the following parameters in local.conf:
 - PHYSICAL_DEVICE_MAPPINGS (For Example: default:eth1)
    or
   PHYSICAL_NETWORK (For Example: default) + PHYSICAL_INTERFACE (For Example: eth1)
- Q_PLUGIN=ml2
- Q_MECHANISM_DRIVER=sriovnicswitch
- PCI_PASSTHROUGH_WHITELIST (see the example below)
Example of Configure PCI_PASSTHROUGH_WHITELIST:
[[post-config|$NOVA_CONF]]
[DEFAULT]
pci_passthrough_whitelist = {"address":"*:02:00.*","physical_network":"default"}

q-agt should be true(I.E: enable_service q-agt).

For more information About SRIOV: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/SR-IOV-Passthrough-For-Networking

Change-Id: Idc502adac6cc296bf1f3256c3ca6637adccfd9c3

commit_message:
Add resource tag to logging in volume.manager.py

We now have resource tag support in oslo logging,
and our logging is pretty inconsistent and down right
ugly in places.  Let's clean things up based on the
standard logging guidelines and use the fancy new
resource tag.

To use set the following in cinder.conf:
logging_context_format_string = \
%(asctime)s.%(msecs)03d %(levelname)s %(name)s [%(request_id)s \
%(project_name)s] %(resource)s%(message)s

This change hits the majority of the code in manager and
should be used as an example/guide.  There are some exceptions
around migration and replication where things are kinda ugly,
those should be fixed up as follow up work.

Change-Id: I1315cc16116601fea8c023b47f99b2eaad01d6fb

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-14 06:48:52.000000000', 'message': "Allow discrete blocks of online pCPUs for pinning

Currently, the check for cpu pinning is a little broad and
it doesn't allow pinning for discrete online pcpu sets if the
cpuset ID exceeds the total number of online pcpus.

The fix is for NUMA topology enabled hosts, where the list of
online pcpus are obtained and compared with the list of IDs which
are requested as a part of cpu pinning. If the IDs form a subset
of the total available pcpus on the host, pinning is allowed.
If not, old behavior is retained.

Change-Id: I8cbd938f99e1eae9eeaa3bb27f492c95734bbfab
Closes-Bug: #1442546

commit_message:
libvirt: Allow discrete online pCPUs for pinning

Currently, the check for cpu pinning is a little broad and
it doesn't allow pinning for discrete online pcpu sets if the
cpuset ID exceeds the total number of online pcpus.

The fix is for NUMA topology enabled hosts, where the list of
online pcpus are obtained and compared with the list of IDs which
are requested as a part of cpu pinning. If the IDs form a subset
of the total online pcpus on the host, pinning is allowed.
If not, old behavior is retained.

Change-Id: I8cbd938f99e1eae9eeaa3bb27f492c95734bbfab
Closes-Bug: #1442546

commit_message:
Fix migrate_flavor_data() to catch instances with no instance_extra rows

The way the query was being performed previously, we would not see any
instances that didn't have a row in instance_extra. This could happen if
an instance hasn't been touched for several releases, or if the data
set is old.

The fix is a simple change to use outerjoin instead of join. This patch
includes a test that ensures that instances with no instance_extra rows
are included in the migration. If we query an instance without such a
row, we create it before doing a save on the instance.

Closes-Bug: #1447132
Change-Id: I2620a8a4338f5c493350f26cdba3e41f3cb28de7

commit_message:
libvirt: use importutils instead of python built-in

oslo_utils some routines to handle module importation, we
should use them in our code base insteadof invoking
the private built-in __import__

Change-Id: I5647ec4864e6202e7886c2923cdde30f8736ae29

To make the script more flexible to include more or less tests,
Allow the test regex to be defined prior to calling to post_test_hook.sh.

Change-Id: Id64d761e7ad035a2e6d6351b04b9f224aa3b8e86

commit_message:
Allow overriding the manila test regex

To make the script more flexible to include more or less tests,
Allow the test regex to be defined prior to calling to post_test_hook.sh.

This will also allow the various jenkins jobs to define the regex directly
instead of relying on their name.

Change-Id: Id64d761e7ad035a2e6d6351b04b9f224aa3b8e86

Also, as per a comment on the parent change, when can you see the need for having more than 2 FakeMachine's created by a PeerMachines instance?  Even if the FakeMachine instances where on separate networks (whatever that means), I'm not sure there is a point to validating connectivity between more than 2 endpoints. Replace BaseIPVethTestCase by FakeMachine

This change removes BaseIPVethTestCase class and moves Pinger class to
allow its use from a fake machine.

Change-Id: I0636f11a327e9535828e7b52e60195e52831a0b2

commit_message:
Add --locals to subunit.run

This commit adds the --locals flag to the subunit.run command to enable
showing frame local variables in tracebacks.

Change-Id: I76c716ce4c2b354efde5c88d07852fee77a30a33

commit_message:
Add external genconfig calls

After moving to oslo.config we still were using
incubator config generator.  This was ok, but the
problem is we haven't been pulling config options
from the oslo libs.

This is a hack that just appends external lib calls
and appends those options to the sample file being built.

Change-Id: I2634b20ef4abd3bf7990f845d59ad3d208db234f
(cherry picked from commit 51a22591a44932463847ed3247899db32ac49444)
Closes-Bug: #1447380

commit_message:
Fix MismatchError to nondeterministic order for list of controllers

The list of controllers returned by the ovsdb server can be in any order,
therefore we can't assert likes for likes. Assert the sorted lists instead.

Change-Id: Ice3bb8cc0b3da70f8c9aae50d8cdae2b474ff49b
Closes-bug: #1448202

[{'created': '2015-04-24 08:41:09.000000000', 'message': "Don't resync on DHCP agent setup failure

There are various cases where the DHCP agent will try to
create a DHCP port for a network and there will be a failure.
This has primarily been caused by a lack of available IP addresses
in the allocation pool. However, even if we put a significant
effort into making sure the subnet always has IP availability,
there may be failures related to other constraints of ML2 mechanism
drivers, etc. Ultimately, we need to make the DHCP agent robust to
the failure to create a port.

This patch adds logic to catch repeated failures to setup a port on a
network rather that triggering an entire DHCP resync over and over.
This will leave DHCP broken for that network until the next retry
when a port is created on the network or a subnet or network is updated.

Change-Id: I0896730126d6dca13fe9284b4d812cfb081b6218
Closes-Bug: #1447883

commit_message:
Don't resync on DHCP agent setup failure

There are various cases where the DHCP agent will try to
create a DHCP port for a network and there will be a failure.
This has primarily been caused by a lack of available IP addresses
in the allocation pool. Trying to fix all availability corner cases
on the server side will be very difficult due to race conditions between
multiple ports being created, the dhcp_agents_per_network parameter, etc.

This patch just stops the resync attempt on the agent side if a failure
is caused by an IP address generation problem. Future updates to the subnet
will cause another attempt so if the tenant does fix the issue they will
get DHCP service.

Change-Id: I0896730126d6dca13fe9284b4d812cfb081b6218
Closes-Bug: #1447883

commit_message:
Refactor socket ssl wrapping

Move socket wrapping into a separate method in order to separate
its logic from other action done in _get_socket. Now, ssl wrapping
is applied to the socket returned by _get_socket method.
Additionally checks for ssl config options are now performed during
init and not each time wrap_socket is called.

Added unit tests.

Related-Bug: #1276694
Change-Id: I706517ae351a7a681623ec91c9657a2f61cd2679

commit_message:
Fix L3 agent functional tests random failures

The test_ha_router_failover tests were not being unmocked. This
is because the same object was being mocked twice, but unmocked
once. The mock.patch.stopall call in the tests base class was rewinding
the value of the object from the second mock to the first mock.

Follow up tests in the same worker were using namespace
names defined via the first mock in the failover test.

Closes-Bug: #1446261
Change-Id: I8f24b8bb3a6a501dbe210c2cc67c47fa4b76257c

commit_message:
Install glean from openstack source

glean is now moved into the openstack-infra repos, so the reference to
the originally temporary home can be discarded.

Change-Id: Ie89fff85e264a36d9bab15801314d5195b45031c

commit_message:
Apply a naming rule of GET to telemetry client

[GET /resources] methods should be "list_<resource name>s"
or "show_<resource name>", so this patch applies the rule
to telemetry client.

Partially implements blueprint consistent-service-method-names

Change-Id: I9b5cabf1507c3ba5ad9538b5cd2ee2be5aa29939

commit_message:
Make the storage layer more resilent to failures

When a storage failure happens the internally maintained
flow detail or atom details should not be updated; to ensure
this happens update a cloned atom/flow detail first and only
if the save succeeds do we update the internal version (and
perform any futher work).

Change-Id: Ib8da476b6be2c71b663e0fc659b5df24e6b9f095

commit_message:
Add a conductor running example

Create an example which can be extended to create a simplistic
review checkout, tox running system which can be used to run
some set of actions on every review posted. This could be expanded
and connected into a gerrit pipeline to create a mini-jenkins
like trigger/build/result system.

Part of ongoing blueprint more-examples

Change-Id: I5cf1bf02eeddf897ac7f098f1d73377f262a267b

I have question: why do you need possibility to setup neutron-api-specific data more than in one place? There is only one Neutron can be in cloud, hence, only one set of data will be required.

Then, no test coverage for change. It is not verified. All menioned "three" cases are not tested.

And, finally, mentioned "network plugin" is not related to this change. Opts that are considered within this change are "neutron-api" opts, that specify info for connecting to neutron. It is different than in "network plugins", that describe "how" network resources should be used. commit_message:
Add config_group_name for NeutronNetworkHelper

Manila is designed to look for network config options in the order by
network_config_group, the share backend's config group and
'DEFAULT' group.

Currently, only 'DEFAULT' group has been searched by NeutronNetworkHelper.

Closes-Bug: #1439030

Change-Id: Id84d415766daa1fc2cec26fc03c2678eaeb00968

commit_message:
Adding get_quotas to utils/openstack/nova.py

In order to check quotas in Sahara is necessary to recover them from
nova. This patch creates the necessary methods to retrieve this
information.

Partial-bug:#1174612

Change-Id: I4ccd0f1a4cdd0367f0d22234cb22301c5742112c

commit_message:
Remove precise functests for diskimage-builder

Looks like this doesn't work and we'll need to make a decision about
either fixing it or documenting that building on precise is unsupported.
Meanwhile we can't have all our patches failing checks.

Change-Id: If550dda79af875998041da2ed5251e6e9a1d84f7

commit_message:
Add Ironic maintenance state pass-through

Adding methods to Shade to support controlling the node maintenance
state in Ironic via new methods set_machine_maintenace_state and
remove_machine_from_maintenance.

Basic tests added for both methods.

Change-Id: I50e7f55199992228c0417c98d18a6e63588cd03d

commit_message:
added check for delay >= timeout in LB update monitor

In network loadbalancer, while updating health monitor
the value of 'delay' should be greater than or equal
to 'timeout' value.

This should be catched before submitting the form
but in the current implementation the form is just
submitted and displaying the generic error 'unable
to update monitor'

This patch is checking this condition and displaying
the specific error without submitting the form.

Change-Id: I13e47b1e6871be87d8887ea6a9bc67195663a229
Closes-Bug: #1448115

commit_message:
Fix max_number for migrate_flavor data

The max_number was not being set correctly due to mapping from
--max-number onto max_number in the params not being set up.

Also the migrate_flavor_data db API doesn't require a max-number to
process. If None is given all instances will have their flavor data
migrated. Support this option by not requiring the --max-number
param from the cli.

Change-Id: Ic2ded8d498b34cb1212fb6fa1c8f1a60f0581a76

Nice catch, we need to add the [keystone_authtoken] section. But the [auth] section is also needed (see cloudkitty/orchestrator.py).

I'm not sure that we can merge auth sections, they have different meaning and might need multiple users.

Thanks."}, {'account_id': 8290, 'date': '2015-04-24 08:34:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hi Gauvain Pocentek, thanks for your review :), yeah you are right, my mistake. after a check, I found that the [keystone_authtoken] section define the authentication info of user requests to cloudkitty API, and will be validated by keystone middleware in API request pipline (cloudkitty haven implemented the api paste configuration yet). The [auth] section define the authentication info when cloudkitty-processor invoke other project's client and in cloudkitty, as for cloudkitty, the "other project's client" is only keystone's client (see /cloudkitty/orchestrator.py) and used to get tenant list. so we should keep the two sections. There is another format that this auth info can get from OS's environ, like this: http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/ceilometer/tree/ceilometer/service.py#n51'}, {'account_id': 8290, 'date': '2015-04-24 08:36:55.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-24 08:52:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

this bp just try to implement this change in Nova API, personally, I think this is also valuable for Nova.

Hi John Garbutt, thanks for your review.

liusheng'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2014-07-16 11:42:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-2

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-17 19:10:32.000000000', 'message': 'remove downgrade support from our database migrations

The TC approved a cross project spec to stop putting db downgrade into
project migration repos:
https://github.com/openstack/openstack-specs/blob/master/specs/no-downward-sql-migration.rst
This was done after quite a bit of feedback from the operator
community, and everyone was good with it.

This implements that spec for Nova, adjust the tests to pass
accordingly, and changes the test which requires downgrade functions

commit_message:
remove downgrade support from our database migrations

The TC approved a cross project spec to stop putting db downgrade into
project migration repos:
https://github.com/openstack/openstack-specs/blob/master/specs/no-downward-sql-migration.rst
This was done after quite a bit of feedback from the operator
community, and everyone was good with it.

This implements that spec for Nova, adjust the tests to pass
accordingly, and changes the test which requires downgrade functions
to one that prohibits them.

Implements bp nova-no-downward-sql-migration

Change-Id: I9b164b748998530d62bbc6baf356a9c3f61584cc

commit_message:
Add a limit option to image list

Currently, there is no way to list more than 25 (paging & limit
default value) images.
This patch adds the ability to specify a 'limit' option.

Change-Id: I75cfe29c7e87295df45fe2368cc8d638ba8dd12e
Closes-Bug: 1443089

commit_message:
Windows: Improve vhdutils error messages

The Windows Cinder volume drivers use Win32 API functions for VHD/X
related operations. In case of failure, those return non-zero error
codes.

We can use the FormatMessage function in order to retrieve more
accurate error descriptions based on the error codes.

Change-Id: Ic0d68fe57847c6b1875567873a60315ba7c6d436

[{'created': '2015-04-22 05:47:36.000000000', 'message': "Remove force check from copy_volume_to_image

The upload_volume_to_image method allows a force parameter that will
upload a volume even though the volume is attached/in-use. A user can
get away with this with the LVM driver because the LVM backing is
local to the Cinder worker node that's pushing the bits to Glance.

The problem is, this only works for local storage, it won't work
with any iSCSI devices because they can't do multi-attach. Also,
the reason we required that a volume NOT be in-use for this
operation is because we have no way of keeping the guest Instance
from writing to the volume while we're uploading, and corrupting the data.

This has been exposed like this for several releases, so removing it
now likely would not be a good user experience.  Instead, this
patch add a config option to enable/disable it (default is to
disable), and deployers can choose whether they would like to
allow the use of --force True or not.

commit_message:
Remove force check from copy_volume_to_image

The upload_volume_to_image method allows a force parameter that will
upload a volume even though the volume is attached/in-use. A user can
get away with this with the LVM driver because the LVM backing is
local to the Cinder worker node that's pushing the bits to Glance.

The problem is, this only works for local storage, it won't work
with any iSCSI devices because they can't do multi-attach. Also,
the reason we required that a volume NOT be in-use for this
operation is because we have no way of keeping the guest Instance
from writing to the volume while we're uploading, and corrupting the data.

This has been exposed like this for several releases, so removing it
now likely would not be a good user experience.  Instead, this
patch add a config option to enable/disable it (default is to
disable), and deployers can choose whether they would like to
allow the use of --force True or not.

DocImpact Disables the --force option to copy-volume-to-image and
          introduces "allow_force_upload" boolean option to re-enable

Change-Id: I1210186689dea204601356f8d08805c6cb6f017c
Closes-Bug: 1446954

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-03-30 17:48:35.000000000', 'message': 'Allow explicit numa pinning in flavor extra specs or image metadata

There are cases where the host compute nodes may have software services or
hardware that are associated with a specific NUMA node. For high-performance
guests to make use of these services the software in the guest should run on
virtual NUMA nodes that are explicitly mapped to the desired host NUMA nodes.
In order to allow this, the proposal is to allow explicitly specifying this
mapping via flavor extra specs of the form "hw:numa_node.X = Y", or image
metadata of the form "hw_numa_node.X=Y" where X is the integer numa node in
the guest, and Y is the integer numa node on the host.

APIImpact

Implements blueprint numa-node-pinning

As currently envisioned it wouldn't directly change the API, but it would give
meaning to the above flavor extra specs and image metadata.  Also, it would
add to the list of expected exceptions in the self.compute_api.create() call
in api/openstack/compute/plugins/v3/servers.py.

Change-Id: Ic7286f4901722a471aeac67cc43bfc699507cfd7

commit_message:
Allow explicit numa pinning in flavor extra specs or image metadata

There are cases where the host compute nodes may have software services or
hardware that are associated with a specific NUMA node. For high-performance
guests to make use of these services the software in the guest should run on
virtual NUMA nodes that are explicitly mapped to the desired host NUMA nodes.
In order to allow this, the proposal is to allow explicitly specifying this
mapping via flavor extra specs of the form "hw:numa_node.X = Y", or image
metadata of the form "hw_numa_node.X=Y" where X is the integer numa node in
the guest, and Y is the integer numa node on the host.

APIImpact

Implements blueprint numa-node-pinning

As currently envisioned it wouldn't directly change the API, but it would give
meaning to the above flavor extra specs and image metadata.  Also, it would
add to the list of expected exceptions in the self.compute_api.create() call
in api/openstack/compute/plugins/v3/servers.py.

Change-Id: Ic7286f4901722a471aeac67cc43bfc699507cfd7

commit_message:
[install-guide] Specify lock_path option

The lock_path option moved from the [DEFAULT] section to
the [oslo_concurrency] section in several services. However,
some distributions did not update their configuration files
to reflect this change. In these cases, we must explicitly
add this option in the correct location to prevent
deprecation warnings.

Update this patch to address additional services with this
issue.

Change-Id: I208223e60dd86f9e4c753b52a2faaf240209b674
Implements: blueprint installguide-kilo

commit_message:
Move wait_for_status to resource module

wait_for_status is a function that is useful to many resources such as
volumes, stacks, databases, servers, and images. It would useful to have a
generic utility function to wait on the status of any such resource.

In the resource proxies the wait_for functions are named specifically to
that resource (e.g. compute.v2._proxy.wait_for_server) to stay consistent
with the verb_resource naming convention.

Change-Id: I6290235a9f7b0c204fc3933bf35497d0d8c4d0fe

commit_message:
Run the glance cache cron jobs more frequently

Currently, running every 24 hours is long enough to allow the cache to
completely fill up the container's disk. By running the jobs every 6
hours instead (4 times per day), we hope to eliminate the problem where
the container will fill up.

Closes-bug: 1439892
Change-Id: Ie7311f70656447382c2403e79453fe88401efca1
(cherry picked from commit 83f0d59191dc2afe9cbfbb8bf255edd4134446a7)

commit_message:
Update Horizon configuration

Additional feature changes have been made since we last updated our
template file. This brings our configuration file in line with the
example.

During Liberty, one of these changes related to execeptions will
likely need to be revised but for now this is the correct way of
handling them.

commit_message:
Update the rest of the code to satisfy flake8 in a py34 env

* Use six.moves.reduce
* Update numliteral from 0L to 0
* Use open() instead of file()
* Use rich comparison methods instead of cmp()

partial blueprint heat-python34-support

Change-Id: I9ffd85645563192b5d6124f8dbb71c24245eefc4

commit_message:
Run the glance cache cron jobs more frequently

Currently, running every 24 hours is long enough to allow the cache to
completely fill up the container's disk. By running the jobs every 6
hours instead (4 times per day), we hope to eliminate the problem where
the container will fill up.

Conflicts:
	playbooks/roles/os_glance/tasks/glance_post_install.yml

Closes-bug: 1439892
Change-Id: Ie7311f70656447382c2403e79453fe88401efca1
(cherry picked from commit 83f0d59191dc2afe9cbfbb8bf255edd4134446a7)

commit_message:
Run the glance cache cron jobs more frequently

Currently, running every 24 hours is long enough to allow the cache to
completely fill up the container's disk. By running the jobs every 6
hours instead (4 times per day), we hope to eliminate the problem where
the container will fill up.

Closes-bug: 1439892
Change-Id: Ie7311f70656447382c2403e79453fe88401efca1

commit_message:
Set external roles to import into ansible namespace

This patch sets the ansible external roles to export into the ansible
namespace (/etc/ansible/roles) instead of the os-ansible-deployment namespace.

This ensures a seperation of concerns and simplifies the os-ansible-deployment
upgrade process.

Partially implements: blueprint master-kilofication
Change-Id: I96dd61a4d3bdc52ae577fbf006387ffac58b7875

commit_message:
Fixes cyclic ref detection in project subtree

The code was improperly using sets to detect circular references. This
was not caught because there were no tests to exercise the behavior.

Change-Id: Ie8dbd3567717ad63a3852d46367bb879dbe81472
Closes-Bug: #1446834

commit_message:
made all status values translatable in volume table

In volume, snapshot and backup tables, all the value of the status column are not translatable,
since some of the status values are missing in the display choice tuple.

This patch adding the missing status values in the display choice tuple.

Change-Id: I6990fd8bfd58156be00b4a47d6dc8ca6cc12f408
Closes-Bug: #1447928

(6 comments)

Posted some specific comments inline. In addition to that, some thoughts on changing the API interface here.

- Heat has an established user base, so we must be very cautious event on the smallest changes, e.g. data type validation;
- We'd better work with the API-WG to come up with some API micro-versioning schema. Even if there is no global guidelines for this, we can at least learn something from Nova's practices;
- Before API versioning plan is there, maybe we should keep the API as is unless there is a compelling reason to change;
- All changes should be reflected at the api-site because the document should be the only source of information for any maturing software.
- Finally, we need a version negotiation mechanism from both the server and the client side.

That said, I still believe this patch is proposing some useful features."}, {'account_id': 10487, 'date': '2015-04-02 08:05:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Workflow-1

commit_message:
Add basic orchestration tests to the gate check

This change adds a "heat_api" test list that includes a few
basic orchestration api tests. To make it easier to build test
sets, the openstack_tempest_gate.sh script now accepts
multiple test lists as arguments, which are combined into a
single master list. The default test set for the gate check now
includes the "scenario" and "heat_api" lists.

Change-Id: I51d5a7c47c3b5ff6a12f7ebccb0f40afa571c3d0
(cherry picked from commit 4606914317512edeab097fcbe0504d0d6d3211ef)

commit_message:
Update Horizon configuration

Additional feature changes have been made since we last updated our
template file. This brings our configuration file in line with the
example.

During Liberty, one of these changes related to execeptions will
likely need to be revised but for now this is the correct way of
handling them.

(cherry picked from commit 9e01ff316f7814e7b81362b49f7cbb8259d18979)

commit_message:
Add package list and repos to AIO diagnostics

This patch adds a listing of installed packages to the AIO diagnostic output
to assist with determining package conflicts in OpenStack CI.

(cherry picked from commit c89ce709cc48312d82767cc1791c643a5e380866)

commit_message:
Port ZMQ driver to Python 3

* Fix bytes/unicode issues in the ZMQ driver
* Add pyzmq test dependency on Python 3
* Enable (indirectly) ZMQ driver tests on Python 3

Change-Id: I812f1ec7ad2dcd8e16af70d6f8f9bc3cf7a2225c
Depends-on: I0efae1c91c5d830156b867d7d21b5c0065094665

costs in multinode setup. It runs host and workspace setup in parallel
as well as running devstack setup in parallel. Some portions of
multinode setup like the network overlay configuration is not yet done
in ansible, but doing that in parallel is less pressing as the cost is
much lower.

This does also try to establish some conventions around using ansible in
d-g. Control flow logic should remain in bash with d-g. All shell
variables should be interpolated into the ansible command strings before
running ansible (do not pass through to the remote side), this keeps
commands simple and avoids surprises with values being picked up
differently on the remote side. This may have to change over time as we
use ansible more, but for now this seems to work well.

Follow up changes should look at using ansible playbook for colocated
ansible commands. We should also convert more of the cross node setup
into ansible.

commit_message:
Make multinode first class with ansible

Use ansible to get work done in parallel because we want to make
devstack-gate treat multinode testing as a first class citizen.

Note that this is just a first iteration that covers the largest time
costs in multinode setup. It runs host and workspace setup in parallel
as well as running devstack setup in parallel. Some portions of
multinode setup like the network overlay configuration is not yet done
in ansible, but doing that in parallel is less pressing as the cost is
much lower.

This does also try to establish some conventions around using ansible in
d-g. Control flow logic should remain in bash with d-g. All shell
variables should be interpolated into the ansible command strings before
running ansible (do not pass through to the remote side), this keeps
commands simple and avoids surprises with values being picked up
differently on the remote side. This may have to change over time as we
use ansible more, but for now this seems to work well.

Follow up changes should look at using ansible playbook for colocated
ansible commands. We should also convert more of the cross node setup
into ansible.

Change-Id: I34cec44281eadfbfb990ed8ed160ee7dec50341b

commit_message:
Set gerrit default branch to kilo

This adds an entry to .gitreview to set the default branch to kilo for the
kilo branch. This is a convenience to allow 'git review' to be done without
specifying the target branch when working from the particular branch.

Change-Id: I2d1b8b9b1c94ca1525e848e2a4050b5c0a0b96bf

I'm not totally sure how we dropped the ball on https://review.openstack.org/#/c/150352/ - but there were a lot of these and they were fairly mechanical.  I think in other changes like this it was OK because the policy.json wasn't configurable for an extension so we'd have to default to admin in v2 API in some cases, but that's not the case here:

http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/nova/tree/etc/nova/policy.json#n83

I wonder if using the real policy file rather than the fake on in the tests would have caught this?

http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/nova/tree/nova/tests/unit/fake_policy.py#n232"}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2015-04-22 19:48:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Control create/delete flavor api permissions using policy.json

The permissions of create/delete flavor api is currently broken
and expects the user to be always an admin, instead of controlling
the permissions by the rules defined in the nova policy.json.

Change-Id: Ide3c9ec2fa674b4fe3ea9d935cd4f7848914b82e
Closes-Bug: 1445335
