commit_message:
Finish support of benchmarking with existing users

Now one can use Rally for benchmarking OpenStack clouds that are using
LDAP, AD or any other read only keystone backend where you are not able
to create any users.

To do this one can specify "users" section in ExistingCloud plugin
input file.

Rally will use these "users" to generate load instead of creating new.
As well if you specify both "users" section in deployment input file
and "users" context it will use temporary created by Rally users.

Restructurize samples/deployments directory:

  - Deploying OpenStack clouds with Rally is not popular functionallity
    so hide all samples deeper.
  - Some fixes in readme.rst
  - Add new sample for existing cloud with predefined users

Change-Id: If3d31960ee317e0770abceacc62b3acf0947d269

commit_message:
[install-guide] make Swift workable for kilo

* specify version 3.0 for authentication
* use correct URLs for sample configuration files
* update/add output of commands
* add modules to improve functionality
* update keystone middleware to use identity v3 api

Partially implements bp installguide-kilo

Co-Authored-By: Matt Kassawara <mkassawara@gmail.com>
Change-Id: I185b3110260ca2fb1d42a3612ac6c074f63fd4cc

commit_message:
Run Gnocchi devstack tests for stable/1.0 against Kilo

Gnocchi is doing more releases than most OpenStack projects so there's
no e.g. stable/kilo branch. We need to do a mapping here so test-matrix
is not completely lost.

commit_message:
Make devstack install obey soft requirements

Despite setting REQUIREMENTS_MODE=soft, devstack
install still fails if you try to install packages
that aren't in global-requirements. This patch
adds a function to lib/solum to override one in
devstack to honor soft_requirements. In our case,
docker-py is a requirement of nova-docker.

Change-Id: I5958aed3dc403b267b549f0f46e92a988f0f8c27

commit_message:
Adopt new spec process for Liberty

Our current spec process has a lot of fundamental flaws. I've tried to
capture as many of these as I could in the opening section of the
blueprint.rst file. I've also modified the process for submitting specs
to move to a feature request model, a slimmed down spec, and a beefed
up devref requirement. The intent is to allow for faster converfence on
ideas, and better in-tree documentation which will lead to better user
facing documentation.

Change-Id: If6475bcd36ac563368a89acb1c2a305be7a1266e

commit_message:
streams definition POST, GET, GET (id), DELETE

This depends on ansible-monasca-schema changes here:
https://github.com/hpcloud-mon/ansible-monasca-schema/pull/17

Here are sample curl commands for POST, GET, and DELETE:
curl -i -X POST -H 'X-Auth-User: mini-mon' -H 'X-Auth-Token: 8c959d0296344c27a47b8e78dbf912ac' -H 'X-Auth-Key: password' -H 'Accept: application/json' -H 'User-Agent: python-monascaclient' -H 'Content-Tye: application/json' -d '{"fire_criteria": [{"event_type": "compute.instance.create.start"}, {"event_type": "compute.instance.create.end"}], "description": "provisioning duration", "name": "panda", "group_by": ["instance_id"], "expiration": 3, "select": [{"traits": {"tenant_id": "406904"}, "event_type": "compute.instance.create.*"}], "fire_actions": ["ed469bb9-2b4a-457a-9926-9da9f6ac75da"], "expire_actions":["ed469bb9-2b4a-457a-9926-9da9f6ac75da"]}' http://127.0.0.1:8080/v2.0/events/stream-definitions

curl -i -X GET -H 'X-Auth-User: mini-mon' -H 'X-Auth-Token: 8c959d0296344c27a47b8e78dbf912ac' -H 'X-Auth-Key: password' -H 'Accept: application/json' -H 'User-Agent: python-monascaclient' -H 'Content-Type: application/json' http://127.0.0.1:8080/v2.0/events/stream-definitions/

curl -i -X DELETE -H 'X-Auth-User: mini-mon' -H 'X-Auth-Token: 8c959d0296344c27a47b8e78dbf912ac' -H 'X-Auth-Key: password' -H 'Accept: application/json' -H 'User-Agent: python-monascaclient' -H 'Content-Type: application/json' http://127.0.0.1:8080/v2.0/events/stream-definitions/86177f0e-f811-4c42-a91a-1813251bf93f

Note: the limit parameter is passed into the streams_repository method for listing streams, but not yet used. We will open a separate Jira to to handle pagination with a user input limit parameter.

Note: fixed a few events problems. stevedore wasn't loading the driver, and missing some abstact function defs.  I tested stream-defintions and events, they both work now.  Had to change the URI for stream-definitions because it conflicted with events, and now is more RESTful.
Change-Id: I0b6dc385e1d095c1bd33867a038fe170ca277bfe

commit_message:
Port centos-minimal to yum-minimal

Now that we have a generic yum-minimal element, just use it in centos
instead of rinse. Adding base as an element-provides of yum-minimal
because this element conflicts with the base element.

Co-Authored-By: Gregory Haynes <greg@greghaynes.net>

Change-Id: I15275d821781171c118f21aa0c0bca55f65a65b3

Clint wrote:
> You may want to mark it WIP.

This change depends on a change on requirements which is currently blocked by the kilo freeze. Isn't it enough?

> I checked it out, ran 'tox -epy34', and after fixing tox.ini, was greeted with a failure of qpid-python, which seems to not be python3 compatible.

I guess that you modified dependencies or installed qpid outside tox, because "tox -e py34" pass here.

I'm working on other changes to enable more tests on Python 3 (I just sent a pull request for redis, I'm working on a patch for zmq but tests are failing). This change is specific to the eventlet executor.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-15 10:04:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

While working on ZMQ, I noticed that the futures dependency is now useless on Python 3: concurrent.futures was added to the stdlib in Python 3.2.

I tried to remove the futures dependency on Python 3 but I got a bug from tox:
https://bitbucket.org/hpk42/tox/issue/236/tox-must-create-the-source-distribution

I wrote a patch to fix it:
https://bitbucket.org/hpk42/tox/pull-request/142/issue-236-subcommand_test-rebuilds-sdist/diff

*If* my fix is accepted, we will have to wait for a release.'}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2015-04-15 20:06:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Enable eventlet dependency on Python 3

Bump eventlet to 0.17.3, the first release fully supporting Python 3
with monkey-patching.

Add aioeventlet and trollius dependencies for the aioeventlet
executor on Python 3.

This change enables tests of eventlet and aioeventlet executors on
Python 3.

Add futures to Python 3 dependencies even if it's not needed, it's
required to workaround a bug in tox.

Depends-on: I73e3056b5e8b9ce710c9c2d59fc5be8e03e28d2a
Change-Id: I0efae1c91c5d830156b867d7d21b5c0065094665

commit_message:
Move oslo.messaging to requirements.txt

The gate-keystonemiddleware-python* jobs were failing because
the pycadf in requirements.txt would cause a much newer
oslo.messaging to be installed and then
keystonemiddleware.test_opts.OptsTestCase.test_entry_point would
fail.

The correct version os oslo.messaging is installed when both
pycadf and oslo.messaging are in the same file.

Because pycadf already requires oslo.messaging, oslo.messaging is
already a requirement for keystonemiddleware, so having it in
requirements.txt shouldn't cause problems and not require a minor
version update.

Change-Id: I42e358ac9348d37e494b1de77922c3d6fd215019

commit_message:
Tests use Database fixture

The Database fixture already kept a reference to the engine,
and was already registering the cleanups that the tests were
registering again. All the fixture needed was a method to
recreate the tables.

Also, moved the cleanup in the Database fixture before create_all,
so that it happens even if create_all raises.

Change-Id: I9a65b15289f4c0342383fa1da58bede942ab53aa

[{'created': '2015-04-08 20:24:25.000000000', 'message': "Make troubleshoot work with dracut ramdisks

Currently, calling the troubleshoot function in a ramdisk script
doesn't work as expected on dracut ramdisks.  This adds an alternate
troubleshoot implementation that will behave as intended.

I did not make it conditional on a kernel param as was done in the
original because dracut can behave strangely if you allow it to
continue after an error.  Always dropping to a shell immediately
should be less confusing.

Change-Id: I98000f4ac6d7890b1f44fe4d10394ac0ea332fcb
"}]
commit_message:
Make troubleshoot work with dracut ramdisks

Currently, calling the troubleshoot function in a ramdisk script
doesn't work as expected on dracut ramdisks.  This adds an alternate
troubleshoot implementation that will behave as intended.

I did not make it conditional on a kernel param as was done in the
original because dracut can behave strangely if you allow it to
continue after an error.  Always dropping to a shell immediately
should be less confusing.

Change-Id: I98000f4ac6d7890b1f44fe4d10394ac0ea332fcb

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-24 20:33:38.000000000', 'message': 'Fix bug with policy negation and multiple policies

If negation is applied to an atom that references a different
policy, that negation always succeeds.  The root cause was
that negation caused the evaluation engine to skip over
the logic that runs the evaluation routine within another
policy.  This meant that the evaluation engine could
never prove anything positive in that other policy and
hence the negation always succeeded.

This change routes the logic through the normal evaluation
path.  This ensures that what is inside the negation is
evaluated exactly the same as if it were outside the
negation.

Change-Id: I2d5ceeccf87afd99adfe71c359cf2b5e5cd46b38
Closes-bug: 1448295
'}]
commit_message:
Fix bug with policy negation and multiple policies

If negation is applied to an atom that references a different
policy, that negation always succeeds.  The root cause was
that negation caused the evaluation engine to skip over
the logic that runs the evaluation routine within another
policy.  This meant that the evaluation engine could
never prove anything positive in that other policy and
hence the negation always succeeded.

This change routes the logic through the normal evaluation
path.  This ensures that what is inside the negation is
evaluated exactly the same as if it were outside the
negation.

Change-Id: I2d5ceeccf87afd99adfe71c359cf2b5e5cd46b38
Closes-bug: 1448295

Add package list and repos to AIO diagnostics

This patch adds a listing of installed packages to the AIO diagnostic output
to assist with determining package conflicts in OpenStack CI.

commit_message:
Set tcp_tw_reuse for swift storage hosts

For swift storage hosts we are seeing a lot of connections in TIME WAIT
status, violating nf_conntrack. Setting tcp_tw_reuse should help
alleviate this.

Additionally, in order for tcp_tw_reuse to be set safely we need to
ensure nf_conntrack is loaded.

Change-Id: I4392c4022a9a5a884d07eb6fbf27093f0b16f914
Closes-Bug: #1441363
(cherry picked from commit b4c09dbd6e4d7d60c4f99469a82d093900ab8aa2)

commit_message:
Add ubuntu backports repository to AIO if it's not present

The swift installation process requires access to the Ubuntu backports
repository to install the liberasurecode1 and liberasurecode-dev packages. In
the hpcloud environments used in OpenStack-CI the backport repository is not
implemented, so we need to ensure that it's there if it hasn't already been
configured. This patch does that as part of the AIO bootstrap process.

Additionally, heat now requires python-saharaclient >= 0.9.0 and we bump here
to allow heat to install successfully.

Note that both issues are causing the gate to fail and need to be addressed
together to get a successful gate.

Closes-Bug: #1448126
Closes-Bug: #1448152
Change-Id: I5d8c6f4eb7182129ab22defd70a50d78e7ffe86f

commit_message:
Add post hook file for a functional test gate

Add a post hook file for a functional test gate.  Right now, the
script returns success no matter what.  I'd like to monitor how
it goes and eventually make it live.  I figure changing the script
to return a correct result will be easier than changing the gate.

Change-Id: Ia97ce6cb86902e43c6a9942f7f866a8b7baeccbb

commit_message:
Remove references to venv

Stick to using tox, remove the tools directory since it only
contained references to using venv. Also update a few other
locations that would have otherwise been incorrect.

Change-Id: I7d3e9067256ac0935f07904abcf584d898ac1d6f

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-03-19 20:37:49.000000000', 'message': "Corrections to request logging

There were a couple of minor issues with request logging:

1) the trailing ? was always in the URL even when there were no
   parameters

2) The path didn't include the version (e.g., v3), so you might
   not be able to tell if it's a v2 or v3 request.

These are fixed.

Change-Id: Idb001e78b72adb1b88da20a8652bf152746bf32b
"}, {'created': '2015-03-19 20:45:15.000000000', 'message': "Correct request logging query parameters separator

The trailing ? was always in the URL even when there were no
parameters. Now when there's no parameters there will be no ?.

Change-Id: Idb001e78b72adb1b88da20a8652bf152746bf32b
"}]
commit_message:
Correct request logging query parameters separator

The trailing ? was always in the URL even when there were no
parameters. Now when there's no parameters there will be no ?.

Change-Id: Idb001e78b72adb1b88da20a8652bf152746bf32b

commit_message:
Add logging of account allocation to accounts provider

This commit adds a log message to the locking accounts cred provider
to indicate when it has allocated a set of credentials successfully
from the accounts file. Right now when reading the tempest log file
during a run when using an accounts file there is no way to tell which
accounts where returned by the cred provider. This adds a info log msg
similar to what we log in isolated creds when it creates a new set of
creds. This should make it easier to trace through when credentials are
being allocated from the accounts file.

Change-Id: I82af7a3cba1e62cada94a9f4220666f1733e0575

commit_message:
Set tcp_tw_reuse for swift storage hosts

For swift storage hosts we are seeing a lot of connections in TIME WAIT
status, violating nf_conntrack. Setting tcp_tw_reuse should help
alleviate this.

Additionally, in order for tcp_tw_reuse to be set safely we need to
ensure nf_conntrack is loaded.

Change-Id: I4392c4022a9a5a884d07eb6fbf27093f0b16f914
Closes-Bug: #1441363

commit_message:
Set tcp_tw_reuse for swift storage hosts

For swift storage hosts we are seeing a lot of connections in TIME WAIT
status, violating nf_conntrack. Setting tcp_tw_reuse should help
alleviate this.

Additionally, in order for tcp_tw_reuse to be set safely we need to
ensure nf_conntrack is loaded.

Change-Id: I4392c4022a9a5a884d07eb6fbf27093f0b16f914
Closes-Bug: #1441363

commit_message:
Add python34 unit test job to tempest experiemental

In an effort to get tempest running under python 3.4 we need to be
able to run the unit tests on python 3.4. This commit adds the
python 3.4 unit test job on the experimental queue to start so we
can start test tempest under python 3.4.

Change-Id: I82142e529082187b69e26edbcd7062a3efe25f8f

commit_message:
Entrypoints for commands

Use entrypoints for keystone-all and keystone-manage.

This makes keystone consistent with other projects that
already use entry points, e.g., nova.

Change-Id: Ib8d1a30d9b31d515dd5256896e24ae7b327fff6e

commit_message:
Add functional smoke test for disk-image-create

We do not have any testing inside DIB for testing disk-image-create
logic. Lets do some smoke testing for all our supported image formats.

Also adding a run_functests.sh so we can extend this later without editing
the jenkins job.

Change-Id: Ie491e27f00bde54f73af6b47c9696ec04d973b14

commit_message:
Fix various Networking forms urls

Many URLs in the networking panels don't work correctly when loading the
forms as a page, rather than a modal. This patch correctly reverses the
relevant URLs.

Closes-Bug: 1446708
Change-Id: I2d54e5193bed9dbac24323d40f4aea6e21206489

commit_message:
Change nova_proxy_admin_tenant_name to id

The task manager can be configured with periodic events
that check for the existence of running nova instances.
The events run via a separate admin connection to nova.

Taskmanager.Manager populates the admin client context
with the tenant name provided by nova_proxy_admin_tenant_name
parameter instead of the uuid, which results in an invalid
management url that is composed of the two parameters:
<nova_compute_url>/<nova_proxy_admin_tenant_name>.

Changing tenant_name to tenant_id results in a valid endpoint.

DocImpact
deprecating option 'nova_proxy_admin_tenant_name'
to 'nova_proxy_admin_tenant_id'

Change-Id: Ia1315e41288ab1b24ac402bad15176cb1ae0e5cd
Co-Authored-By: Li Ma <skywalker.nick@gmail.com>
Closes-Bug: #1289101

[{'created': '2015-04-24 03:04:02.000000000', 'message': "Simplify ring.builder.RingBuilder.__deepcopy__

Only container classes (lists, sets, dicts, graphs, collections,
etc) need to track objects they deepcopy in the memo dict -
particularly when they may contain other containers!  As they
recreate a new container with the same items as themselves, they'll
reference the memo for each item they contain before making a
deepcopy of it, and place a reference to the copied item into memo
after they do.  Trying to help out some other container class in
this endeavor by attempting to add ourselves to the memo dict in
some useful manor on their behalf however; is not helpful.

All we need to do to make sure we're being a good __deepcopy__
implementation is make sure we pass on memo to our calls of deepcopy
so that other container classes can avoid making additional
deepcopy's of our containers if they already have a memorized copy
(which would be odd since unique instances of RingBuilders aren't
expected to share state, but hey - python doesn't have private
attributes so you never know!)

Change-Id: Ifac444dffbf79d650b2d858f6282e05d8ea741a0
"}]
commit_message:
Simplify ring.builder.RingBuilder.__deepcopy__

Only container classes (lists, sets, dicts, graphs, collections,
etc) need to track objects they deepcopy in the memo dict -
particularly when they may contain other containers!  As they
recreate a new container with the same items as themselves, they'll
reference the memo for each item they contain before making a
deepcopy of it, and place a reference to the copied item into memo
after they do.  Trying to help out some other container class in
this endeavor by attempting to add ourselves to the memo dict in
some useful manor on their behalf however; is not helpful.

All we need to do to make sure we're being a good __deepcopy__
implementation is make sure we pass on memo to our calls of deepcopy
so that other container classes can avoid making additional
deepcopy's of our containers if they already have a memorized copy
(which would be odd since unique instances of RingBuilders aren't
expected to share state, but hey - python doesn't have private
attributes so you never know!)

Change-Id: Ifac444dffbf79d650b2d858f6282e05d8ea741a0

commit_message:
Mocks out the memcache library for tests

The python-memcache project still has not produced a version of
the library that can be used in Python 3. Now that we have a hard
dependency on it at import time we need to mock it out.

bp python3
Change-Id: I6edb8da7a8c42f8b503684ad2fdfbc3e68410101

commit_message:
Standardize cookbook name to openstack_client

The current cookbook mixed "openstack-client" with "openstack_client"  of
cookbook name in this project.
So this patch standardize cookbook name to openstack_client

Change-Id: I9f2a628fb141cbc2ebcbe3fa075fb1a413be8d1e
Closes-Bug: #1448099

commit_message:
Add testr_results report

Using the env var DEVSTACK_GATE_TEMPEST will add a report with the
passed tests.

DEVSTACK_GATE_TEMPEST_FULL is not needed because in the devstack-gate is
evaluated only if DEVSTACK_GATE_TEMPEST_REGEX is not set, which is.

Change-Id: I6fd119b1669dd8bafeb7c55bbaf87eb49fad592a

commit_message:
Run full tempest on centos7

This should be OK to run full tempest tests.  We've sorted out a
number of issues lately relating to memory and swap usage and making
sure package updates are installed.

Change-Id: I007c7c7ba50f8ea5ab1afe69ab52f6d1be727966

While this does appear to work and it'd be good to have Orchestration testing in the gate check, I find myself thinking that we need to have a more flexible way of compiling a test list to do similar inclusions for network tests, etc. We also need to settle on some consistency for the test list names so that we stop causing trouble for the multi-node gate which is a downstream consumer of the test lists. Can we consider coming up with a similarly dynamic, yet less complex way of doing test selection?"}, {'account_id': 7307, 'date': '2015-04-22 08:34:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I think this is fine as an interim solution, but heat have integration tests in the heat repo itself and I think it'd be better if we could leverage some of these tests so that we're doing an actual 'scenario' style test for orchestration in the on-commit AIO gate rather than testing some arbitrary API call."}, {'account_id': 7307, 'date': '2015-04-22 09:15:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Hi Miguel, see http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-March/060018.html.  I'm wondering if such an approach exists yet?  It'd be nice if we can pull these integration tests into our tempest setup and run from there."}, {'account_id': 12606, 'date': '2015-04-22 14:23:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Matt, I have all of one day of experience working with tempest, so I don't think I'm qualified to answer. To my knowledge there isn't a solution yet.

Jesse, regarding test selection, yes, I actually made the same comment to Kevin in IRC last night, but I think that is less of an emergency. This solves the immediate problem, which is that Heat's auth business is non-standard, so we need to test it. They are making changes in the heat repo around this area, so in my view we need to have something to ensure the basic stuff is working asap. This one test covers it by making a trip to the API and back."}, {'account_id': 12606, 'date': '2015-04-23 01:23:13.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 7353, 'date': '2015-04-23 01:25:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Add basic orchestration tests to the gate check

This change adds a "heat_api" test list that includes a few
basic orchestration api tests. To make it easier to build test
sets, the openstack_tempest_gate.sh script now accepts
multiple test lists as arguments, which are combined into a
single master list. The default test set for the gate check now
includes the "scenario" and "heat_api" lists.

Change-Id: I51d5a7c47c3b5ff6a12f7ebccb0f40afa571c3d0

commit_message:
Removed hard coded package pinning for mariadb/galera

This change removes the hard set package pinning from the upstream
repository. The hard coded nature of this makes it impossible to
maintain over the lifecycle of a given release. While the default
pinning has been removed the ability to pin to whatever the
deployer wants still exists and can be used as the deployer sees
fit.

Conflicts:
      etc/rpc_deploy/user_variables.yml

Change-Id: I94300184f28b9564dedcc7d14f18aa793765ed8f
Closes-Bug: #1446772
(cherry picked from commit 4d4532ec1d322a0886e41b13fcc1d727fd600937)

Well, it seems that Cinder's approach was to change the directory to something in /var/lib/cinder

Wouldn't it make sense to have something similar in Barbican instead of removing this line entirely?"}, {'account_id': 15515, 'date': '2015-04-23 20:31:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

So, from my testing on OS X, what happens when it is undefined is it creates a random folder in /var/folders to put the certs. This makes it exceedingly unlikely that anyone will be able to pre-populate the directory with junk PEM files. There don't seem to be any errors/etc. associated with this approach, and it is the more secure option.

I'm not necessarily 100% against setting a default directory, but I'm guessing it would be harder to find a platform-independent location in /var to house them, that has the right permissions in all situations.

I also found this discussion on the NOVA launchpad about using the same directory: https://bugs.launchpad.net/keystone/+bug/1031022

They say that there's a problem with running multiple instances with the same signing_dir folder defined, so we'd additionally have to account for multiple users/instances.

Here's NOVA's patch when they had the security issue (simply disabled signing_dir): https://review.openstack.org/#/c/28568/1/etc/nova/api-paste.ini

From the signing_dir code in KeystoneMiddleware (https://github.com/openstack/keystonemiddleware/blob/master/keystonemiddleware/auth_token/_signing_dir.py) it looks like the requirements are:
- path must be owned by the user
- must be CHMODed 700"}, {'account_id': 15515, 'date': '2015-04-23 22:30:31.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 15515, 'date': '2015-04-23 22:31:31.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 7789, 'date': '2015-04-23 22:43:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 8623, 'date': '2015-04-23 22:44:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-23 23:19:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified-1

commit_message:
Removing signing_dir directive from config

The signing_dir directive defined in barbican-api-paste.ini explicitly
stores Keystone's signing certificates in a known /tmp directory. This
could be exploited by populating the directory with bogus certificates,
potentially allowing a malicious user to generate valid tokens.

Added comment explaining signing_dir, and a reasonable
(commented) default.

Change-Id: I15fda6863e888e3881694ab47a836eee2fb578ee
Closes-Bug: #1446406

Following up from the IRC discussion. This brings in a few deps that are not needed. It also does not solve any real problems.

Cases of time moving backwards are rare and our use of time here is completely unaffected by it. We will just print an slightly wrong number once every long while.

Even if we were calculating a timeout period the worst case is we would timeout too quickly, but if we have timeouts then we should already be handling timeouts so the super occasional timeout due to time moving backwards should already be handled properly.'}, {'account_id': 4146, 'date': '2015-04-22 23:11:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

On further review oslo.utils depends on time.monotonic existing in the python stdlib or the monotonic lib be installed from pypi. Python 2.7 (where we will run shade most often) does not have time.monotonic from what I can tell and oslo.utils does not depend on and install monotonic. This means the stopwatch falls back to using time.time() which is what we already use.'}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-04-24 18:23:07.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

Ok dokie, I'll leave this be, for another day then! :)"}]

commit_message:
Use a watch that isn't affected by time going backwards

On versions of python that have monotonic time the usage
of the oslo.utils stop watch will ensure that that code is
used vs using time.time which can go backwards if ntpd or
other system time is altered during running tasks.

Change-Id: Ia50a5582e931c80da12a15aa9f8597b44ae57597

commit_message:
Remove duplicate find request in find_resource

Removed duplicate manager.find method call using search argument
display_name that affected any command that searches for a volume by
display_name or any command that searches for non existent volumes.

Change-Id: I86c99b41dd231b058ed3f6d5d78eafe35a111dec
Closes-Bug: #1429102

will add a default image used in Heat's integration tests to Glance.
The URL can be customized with HEAT_TEST_IMAGE_URL option.

Change-Id: I6643c0456f51269b96baa9e6e9c06c2e2de4495e
"}]
commit_message:
Add option to install Heat's test image

Add HEAT_TEST_IMAGE option (defaulting to false), enabling which
will add a default image used in Heat's integration tests to Glance.
The URL can be customized with HEAT_TEST_IMAGE_URL option.

Change-Id: I6643c0456f51269b96baa9e6e9c06c2e2de4495e

commit_message:
Support Unicode in requirements file

Currently, if there's a Unicode char in requirements, pbr fails. There's
no need to fail, we can use io.open() to handle that instead.

Change-Id: I15e0ff87e72e9890781fc1627804f2811bf2ecb2

commit_message:
Create Consistency Group from CG Snapshot CLI

This patch addressed the following:
* Added a new CLI to support creating a CG from a CG snapshot.

cinder consisgroup-create-from-src [--cgsnapshot <cgsnapshot>]
                                   [--name <name>]
                                   [--description <description>]

API patch: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/145952/

Partial-Implements: blueprint consistency-groups-kilo-update
Change-Id: I03cce04e1d43ea72fc53a8bf614ba4f969f6e32e

commit_message:
[install-guide] [yum] install ceilometermiddleware on swift-proxy node

Workaround for https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1214928.

Partially implements bp installguide-kilo.

Change-Id: Idc6efc4e90f9bc63a632e1d4b4f07885716b1099

commit_message:
Add Python 3.4 support

Heat isn't fully compatible with Python 3.4. This spec outlines a process
to add support for Python 3.4 in Heat.

blueprint heat-python34-support

Change-Id: I526c949e8ef5bc8867bd9bbb551e4871a758fd18

[{'created': '2015-04-24 12:50:06.000000000', 'message': "Remove upgraded kernel check for new clusters

- In 6.1 we don't ship packages on ISO and we can't
get kernel version which is to be installed on new nodes.
So check was only left for old clusters

Change-Id: I9adcf6b85f7f3355706007ea7e138b5cea69f4e5
Closes-Bug: #1448005
"}]
commit_message:
Remove upgraded kernel check for new clusters

- In 6.1 we don't ship packages on ISO and we can't
get kernel version which is to be installed on new nodes.
So check was only left for old clusters

Change-Id: I9adcf6b85f7f3355706007ea7e138b5cea69f4e5
Closes-Bug: #1448005

commit_message:
Temtorary disable repo check on CentOS

While bugs #1403088 and #1448114 not fix, repo check test fails after
    deploy cluster. This can affect other tests. We may disable repo
    checker while bugs not fix

Change-Id: Ieefe3042dd33987c66f8e1ec91f611863cdf4ba4
Related-bug: #1403088
Related-bug: #1448114

commit_message:
Update README to work with release tools

The README file needs to have links to the project documentation and bug
tracker in a parsable format in order for some of the release tools
scripts to work (particularly the one that prints the release note
email).

Change-Id: I1b6a550594a691b5682baf44198a13a1009b9e23

commit_message:
Fixes the SQL model tests

The tests were not completely accurate. The expected columns list
didn't need to have all of the columns. Also the defaults for Boolean
columns were not being checked.

Change-Id: I558870792a836ed775da3f683ed1279cc58216b0

commit_message:
Remove project association before removing endpoint group

Since `project_endpoint_group` has a foreign key reference with `endpoint_group`
thus, if we want to remove endpoint_group we need to remove associated
`project_endpoint_group` at first.

The testcase provided can pass even without code changing only beacuse SQLITE
didn't enforce foreign key constraint by default, so endpoint group with project
association can be deleted (needn't delete project association at first)
successfully.

Closes-Bug: #1443765
bp ondelete-cascade

Change-Id: Id685948373ffb37467f336172a085b91c982cbc7

commit_message:
Isolate injection tests

The first injection test was always tainted by the previous tests since
the dependencies where not cleared before the test run. This change
makes sure that there are no dependencies registered at the start of
each test.

Change-Id: Ic2cf1999777cc695dbb34357f9e360ccc74bff3a

Currently keystone will run one flush per controller, which leads to
excessive churn and rollbacks, which can be disruptive to service.

This uses gearman to have the least-busy controller run the flush. It
still may run into problems if the flush takes longer than four hours
but the cleanup script _should_ be exitting before that time is up.

commit_message:
Use gearman to limit token flush to one host

Currently keystone will run one flush per controller, which leads to
excessive churn and rollbacks, which can be disruptive to service.

This uses gearman to have the least-busy controller run the flush. It
still may run into problems if the flush takes longer than four hours
but the cleanup script _should_ be exitting before that time is up.

Note that this will also require changes in the Heat templates to pass
the control Virtual IP in as a gearman.address

Change-Id: Iee7d7541b691f45d0961f2112baebba452c8aecf
Partial-Bug: #141882

commit_message:
Fix s3_token middleware parsing insecure option

The "insecure" option was being treated as a bool when it was
actually provided as a string. The fix is to parse the string to
a bool.

Closes-Bug: 1411063
Change-Id: Id674f40532215788675c97a8fdfa91d4420347b3

commit_message:
Fix s3_token middleware parsing insecure option

The "insecure" option was being treated as a bool when it was
actually provided as a string. The fix is to parse the string to
a bool.

Change-Id: Id674f40532215788675c97a8fdfa91d4420347b3
Closes-Bug: 1411063

[{'created': '2015-04-23 00:26:36.000000000', 'message': 'Remove pysqlite test-requirement dependency

pysqlite is no longer needed with py27 and definitely note needed
in py34. Eliminate this as a test-requirement. This has the added
benefit of eliminating one of the very few libaries that are blocking

Change-Id: I63d5f0473fdfd91b559b47e7dd9ab4c4307a7c03
'}]
commit_message:
Remove pysqlite test-requirement dependency

pysqlite is no longer needed with py27 and definitely note needed
in py34. Eliminate this as a test-requirement. This has the added
benefit of eliminating one of the very few libaries that are blocking
keystone from being python3.4 compatible.

Change-Id: I63d5f0473fdfd91b559b47e7dd9ab4c4307a7c03

commit_message:
L3 DB: Defer port DB subnet lookups

_populate_subnets_for_ports was being called multiple
times for different interface types during the get_routers
process.

This patch eliminates those extra queries by deferring the
subnet information population until after all of the interfaces
have been looked up. Includes a function rename as well to
indicate that a function is only used internally.

Change-Id: Ib46f685d72eb61ecbaa2869e28fb173cd6d49552
Partial-bug: #1445412

commit_message:
Fix call to load_privatekey() when passphrase is None

The original code worked, but breaks with PyOpenSSL 0.15.1,
the version currently used by the gate.

Closes-Bug: #1448193
Change-Id: Iae44f08fa6442e3463e6b552955229f3fd36fbde

The "insecure" option was being treated as a bool when it was
actually provided as a string. The fix is to parse the string to

Closes-Bug: 1411063
Change-Id: Id674f40532215788675c97a8fdfa91d4420347b3
'}]
commit_message:
Fix s3_token middleware parsing insecure option

The "insecure" option was being treated as a bool when it was
actually provided as a string. The fix is to parse the string to
a bool.

Closes-Bug: 1411063
Change-Id: Id674f40532215788675c97a8fdfa91d4420347b3

commit_message:
Fix s3_token middleware parsing insecure option

The "insecure" option was being treated as a bool when it was
actually provided as a string. The fix is to parse the string to
a bool.

Closes-Bug: 1411063
Change-Id: Id674f40532215788675c97a8fdfa91d4420347b3

commit_message:
Fix redirects for fr and ja User Guide

The redirects matches *any* string containing user-guide, so it matched
also /fr/user-guide/content. Change the regex to not match these for
now.

Change-Id: I2aba634697ff0ea40fc398d7d872bf8a2843fddd

commit_message:
Initial setup for command line tests

Created a cli structure for testing command line client.

Part of this involved refactoring the base.py so that it could be
shared between client and command line tests.

Added basic help subcommand tests to show the flow between
behaviors and tests.

Change-Id: Ia3af13e90b3689c0c2ca5447ead0fb7fc33de086

(1 comment)

This seems somewhat confusing to me. We have resource.uuid (what I'd call the resource ID from the user perspective)

heat resource-show <stack id> <resource id>

What you have implemented is:

heat resource-show <stack id> <physical resource id>

If we look at the client:

heat help resource-show

usage: heat resource-show <NAME or ID> <RESOURCE>

Describe the resource.

Positional arguments:

<NAME or ID>  Name or ID of stack to show the resource for.

<RESOURCE>    Name of the resource to show the details for.

I am just curious why physical resource id instead of resource ID? From the command line PoV it seems less consistent."}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2015-04-24 03:15:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Show resource by physical_id

Add possibility to show resource information by
physical_resource_id. It allows to use
physical_resource_id for commands like:
heat resource-show <stack id> <resource id>

Change-Id: I68f47e7a2f56ad8dc0a2e3e361ca053c3bd4135a

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-23 12:38:01.000000000', 'message': 'Add release pinning to galera roles

As both Ubuntu and the MariaDB repositories carry packages with the same
names, apt package pinning is required to ensure that the packages we install
come from the right repository. This patch adds a pinning preference file to
ensure that the packages we install come from the MariaDB repository.

Due to the OpenStack CI images having conflicting packages installed in the
base image, this patch also includes the removal of these packages during the
AIO bootstrap to ensure that the deployment succeeds.

For environments where the same two packages are installed on the hosts prior
to the deployment of os-ansible-deployment, they would need to ensure that the
packages are removed first. This has been seen in environments where
monitoring tooling has installed the packages as a dependancy.

Additionally, the horizon kilo play the package pathlib is required when doing
an offline compress however this package is not a "requirement"
according to the horizon requirements.txt file though within our
implementation horzion needs this dep.

Closes-Bug: #1446772
Change-Id: I5ad0b9010e49832c4f866c0b141e1c035d5f9268
(cherry picked from commit 886fe01edb01b9f21e3576f50711738687b236d9)
'}, {'created': '2015-04-23 13:36:21.000000000', 'message': "Add release pinning to galera roles

As both Ubuntu and the MariaDB repositories carry packages with the same
names, apt package pinning is required to ensure that the packages we install
come from the right repository. This patch adds a pinning preference file to
ensure that the packages we install come from the MariaDB repository.

Due to the OpenStack CI images having conflicting packages installed in the
base image, this patch also includes the removal of these packages during the
AIO bootstrap to ensure that the deployment succeeds.

For environments where the same two packages are installed on the hosts prior
to the deployment of os-ansible-deployment, they would need to ensure that the
packages are removed first. This has been seen in environments where
monitoring tooling has installed the packages as a dependancy.

Additionally, horizon has updated requirements:
 - pathlib
 - scss

Finally, this patch also updates the global requirements and the sha's for all
openstack branches that we're pinned to.

commit_message:
Add release pinning to galera roles

As both Ubuntu and the MariaDB repositories carry packages with the same
names, apt package pinning is required to ensure that the packages we install
come from the right repository. This patch adds a pinning preference file to
ensure that the packages we install come from the MariaDB repository.

Due to the OpenStack CI images having conflicting packages installed in the
base image, this patch also includes the removal of these packages during the
AIO bootstrap to ensure that the deployment succeeds.

For environments where the same two packages are installed on the hosts prior
to the deployment of os-ansible-deployment, they would need to ensure that the
packages are removed first. This has been seen in environments where
monitoring tooling has installed the packages as a dependancy.

Also, the swift installation process requires access to the Ubuntu backports
repository to install the liberasurecode1 and liberasurecode-dev packages. In
the hpcloud environments used in OpenStack-CI the backport repository is not
implemented, so we need to ensure that it's there if it hasn't already been
configured. This patch does that as part of the AIO bootstrap process.

Finally, this patch also updates the global requirements and the sha's for all
openstack branches that we're pinned to.

Closes-Bug: #1446772
Closes-Bug: #1448152
Change-Id: I5ad0b9010e49832c4f866c0b141e1c035d5f9268
(cherry picked from commit 886fe01edb01b9f21e3576f50711738687b236d9)

commit_message:
Add openstack-keystone to pkg-map

This allows installing packaged Keystone on Debian where the name is
keystone and not openstack-keystone.

Change-Id: I4dec4576ad6d49e3e33a053e5d9bee38e09444fb

commit_message:
Delete haproxy_status check from tools_post.rb

harpoxy_status was removed in
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/174034/5
so we need to remove it from tools_post.rb to avoid
false-negative results

Change-Id: I7d5c22502db6d7f13954b69c8402a43f8a2a0df5
Fuel-CI: disable
Close-Bug: #1446296

commit_message:
Add the function of deleting alarm history

Currently the ceilometer-expirer doesn't delete expired AlarmChanges.
Remained AlarmChanges would be cause of wasted disk-space and slow response.
This patch aims to delete AlarmChanges.

This patch adds a new config option:
[database]
alarm_history_time_to_live = -1

Implements: blueprint delete-alarmhistory
DocImpact
Change-Id: Ib6bda6df720cf8514b621bfe13dd3acba941949f

subject: PXE/ISCSI: Call partx after partioning the disk
revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-24 16:25:10.000000000', 'message': "PXE/ISCSI: Call partx after partioning the disk

The _wait_for_disk_to_become_available function from
common/disk_partitioner.py calls fuser to check if the is not being held
by another process, but it doesn't actually check if the partitions of the
device is available after the disk is partitioned. This patch adds a call
to partx -u to make the kernel re-read the partition table of the device
and then list the partitions to verify if they are really available.

Change-Id: Iceee04af624666345eb464a100e51746790a547c
Closes-Bug: #1403887
Co-authored-by: Lucas Alvares Gomes <lucasagomes@gmail.com>
"}]
commit_message:
PXE/ISCSI: Call partx after partioning the disk

The _wait_for_disk_to_become_available function from
common/disk_partitioner.py calls fuser to check if the is not being held
by another process, but it doesn't actually check if the partitions of the
device is available after the disk is partitioned. This patch adds a call
to partx -u to make the kernel re-read the partition table of the device
and then list the partitions to verify if they are really available.

Change-Id: Iceee04af624666345eb464a100e51746790a547c
Closes-Bug: #1403887
Co-authored-by: Lucas Alvares Gomes <lucasagomes@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Merge tasks end with hosts and virtual_ip in gd

To get connectivity from computes and cinders
for firewall tasks change task list for the first step
from end with host to end with virtial_ips for controller
in neutron_gre

Change-Id: I57f143697a91692bae1717e94a9dd9cd8483845f
Closes-Bug: #1446138

Fix ubuntu preferences generation if none Release was found

Don't fail deployment if Release file doesn't
exist in ubuntu repository.

Closes-bug: #1448178

Hey Steve,

Good catch on the copyright (d'oh!)

Should I go ahead and change the secrets default data in anticipation of the change here (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/163564/9/functionaltests/api/v1/functional/test_secrets.py), or should I leave it for now and update it when that change gets merged?

I think the test cases I've included so far constitute most, if not all, of the tests that will fall in the "unauthenticated tests" category. I'll defer to y'all's judgment as far as when to break them into classes (e.g. UnauthedSecretsTestCase). I've been using comments to differentiate "sections", but if the better practice is to break them into classes, I'm totally open to that as well.'}, {'account_id': 15515, 'date': '2015-03-17 20:40:07.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-03-17 22:28:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

commit_message:
Security tests for Secret resources

These tests will attempt CRUD operations on Secret resources, both
with and without (dummy) project ids, and always without valid tokens.
They should all return HTTP 401s. Fixed block comment formatting for
PEP8. Added tests to SecretsUnauthedTestCase class, with 'security'
and 'negative' tags for all tests. Refactored test names to be in line
with rest of Barbican functional tests, and now using behaviors instead
of client calls. Added tests to create and attempt CRUD operations on
real secrets, and with and without real project-id headers.

Change-Id: Iaae76c13dee795c9ff9f99dfdceb139141c0445a

commit_message:
Jshint unused and undef cleanup for accordion_nav, tabs JS

Removing unused and undefined variables in accordion_nav, tabs
javascript. This ensures that once we enable it globally, the
gate will not barf.

Partial-bug: #1438620

commit_message:
Angular table hzSelectAll should be unchecked if table has no rows

The select-all checkbox shouldn't be initially checked if
the table has no rows. This patch fixes that bug.

(Pulled from gate, can't pass check)

Change-Id: Ib8526953bdf445dc14e1da74fc9df2773e5bc138
Closes-Bug: #1447685

commit_message:
Adds missing text in RST file, End User Guide

This patch adds the following changes:

1. Section Upload and manage images: *OpenStack Virtual
Machine Image Guide* - removed visible tags **;
2. Changed Image Service to Image service (according to the
latest Conventions updates);
3. Section Upload Images:
a) Added all the parameters from the initial xml table,
b) fixed broken enumeration.

Change-Id: Ic73d00c4467e070a0e80668ae5e2321bf2ef3d7e
Closes-Bug: #1447090

commit_message:
MySQL: change default MySQL collate to utf8_general_ci

Install & configure MySQL database by using utf8_general_ci collation
which is the way documented in OpenStack [1] and already the default
in puppetlabs-mysql [2].

[1] http://goo.gl/GA5gyZ
[2] https://github.com/puppetlabs/puppetlabs-mysql/blob/master/manifests/db.pp#L7

Change-Id: I8037d3c1971e4b9bc965a9fd0884e1839585d071
Closes-bug: #1446375
(cherry picked from commit b531066283243a721fa384ba8e6ac2f61dcf76c1)

commit_message:
Disable and mark heartbeat as experimental

Due to some discovered issues since heartbeat is enabled by default.
Specially #1436788, that needs to fix the underlying library, too.
So, according to the discution here:
https://bugs.launchpad.net/oslo.messaging/+bug/1436769/comments/10

We decide to mark the implementation as experimental and disable it by default.

Related-bug: #1436788
Related-bug: #1436769
Change-Id: Ib7c55977f976bdbbc8df4ad5915e0433cbf84a17
(cherry picked from commit 287a4f56f45ed9cd40116a9e7b6e529f3382a925)

[{'created': '2015-04-23 07:26:14.000000000', 'message': "Remove ping check from basic scenario test

ICMP ping was a workaround to proof that a connection between
storage server and VM was working. Since it's now supporting actual
mount operations this is just optional. By default this check is
deactivated.

Change-Id: I0eba48abc4583b2d1a4d690c92137941463730c1
Partially-implements: blueprint scenario-tests
"}]
commit_message:
Remove ping check from basic scenario test

ICMP ping was a workaround to proof that a connection between
storage server and VM was working. Since it's now supporting actual
mount operations this is just optional. By default this check is
deactivated.

Change-Id: I0eba48abc4583b2d1a4d690c92137941463730c1
Partially-implements: blueprint scenario-tests

commit_message:
service child process normal SIGTERM exit

service.py had some code where the child process would catch the
SIGTERM from the parent just so it could exit with 1 status rather
than with an indication that it exited due to SIGTERM. When
shutting down the parent doesn't care in what way the child ended,
only that they're all gone, so this code is unnecessary.

Also, for some reason this caused the child to never exit while
there was an open connection from a client. Probably something
with eventlet and signal handling.

This is a cherry-pick of oslo-incubator commit
702bc569987854b602ef189655c201c348de84cb .

Change-Id: I87f3ca4da64fb8070e4d6c3876a2f1ce1a3ca71d
Closes-Bug: #1446583

commit_message:
Improve iSCSI deployment logs

This patch just add some DEBUG and INFO logs for the iSCSI deployment
methodology, so that the operator knows what's the steps the ramdisk is
taken by looking at the conductor logs.

The patch add logs for Ironic when working with both supported ramdisks
DIB and IPA.

Change-Id: Iaee09643b03877a1a735b6019def47445bf3e16f

commit_message:
OVS_LIB API addition - change bridge controller connection-mode

Add an API to change controller connection mode to 'out-of-band', feature
which might be useful for many projects using Openflow controller with OVS

Change-Id: If93f6858f4eed05f5f1d9bdb1667838d80c490cd
Closes-Bug: #1433208

commit_message:
Send private flag to API

When the --private flag is used, it is not added to the
plan before sending it to the API.

Fixing that issue.

Change-Id: I3411569015868e1cb1e677260e0336423bb5049c

commit_message:
Add corosync failover tests

- Add test to check that in case of corosync node dies
alive rabbit node isn't kicked from cluster
- Add test to check that in case of corosync node dies
dead rabbit node is kicked from cluster

Change-Id: I48b1d80dc81b453d30ca1c66c97b94d215422015
Closes-Bug: #1443827

I'm not going to -2 this, but I'd prefer this to be rebased on my work in https://review.openstack.org/138947."}, {'account_id': 9453, 'date': '2014-12-17 21:28:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

@stevenk - I'm not sure what rebasing this change would achieve. The two changes seem to me to be completely unrelated - I can't see any reason to make this change depend on that change.

The two changes seem to me to not conflict - whichever lands first, I don't believe it will cause the other to have to be re-worked.

I agree that the two changes are about slightly related subject matter but I can't see any reason to make either change dependant on the other.

Could you expand on why you wanted to add a dependancy? I've tested with "git rebase" that it's actually trivial (at least, according to git's algorithms) to rebase this change on top of yours - but perhaps, rather than signifying that the two changes are orthogonal, that just signifies that they conflict in ways that git's limited brain can't detect'}, {'account_id': 9369, 'date': '2014-12-18 04:47:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I was trying to point out that I'm trying hard to wean setup-baremetal off of it's subshelled calls to glance image-create and more passing around shell variables containing the ID of the kernel and the ramdisk, when I've been working on integrating a glance client into os-cloud-config so that register-nodes and setup-flavors can look the IDs up themselves."}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2015-01-05 21:29:01.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-01-05 21:49:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

commit_message:
Set kernel and ramdisk ID for ironic nodes

Ironic has deprecated per-flavor ramdisk and kernel image IDs in favor
of setting them per-node. These parameters are optional to preserve
backward compatibility. For ease of use, the command line client takes
the kernel and ramdisk name and looks up the ID via glance. Also, they
are completely ignored on nova-bm since it does not have a per-node
setting for these ids.

Co-Authored-By: Steve Kowalik <steven@wedontsleep.org>

Change-Id: I702afe81038b6f962ce383edb58227a6015c2a75
Partial-Bug: #1401617

commit_message:
SELinux keepalived read denials

Custom policy to fix read denials seen on overcloud controller node.

Filed bug to upstream selinux-policy for a more permanent fix:
https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1187348

Change-Id: I51b6081642e5fb6c4df1bbaefaffc86cb69fc7ff
Partial-Bug: 1416056

commit_message:
Fix deployment of unprovisioned node in perf tests

After merging I7405ba54d90f6bc986befb5d035b213e4c0f6a73 a bug appear
in performance tests - in one of the tests there was a try to run deploy
on nodes that was "unprovisioned". This fix simulates "provisioned" nodes.

Change-Id: If178ccc9597a2b159082d430f5744aa1220ab5e5
Closes-Bug: #1447949

commit_message:
Fix test_matchmaker_redis on Python 3

redis.smembers(str) returns a list of byte strings.

I missed test failures when I submited my patch to enable redis on
Python 3. I didn't notice that redis tests are skipped when no local
redis server is running.

Change-Id: Ib9ec4e05eb9abd51613f32c93118a1c76649798a

commit_message:
Remove REST links from inventory metadata

In the server_vars / meta / inventory context, the links values have no
use, but they to make the data structure more chatty. Remove them so
that examining the data is more betterer.

Change-Id: Ib84e36a917b3511d59ff2b7aa6ad69712983665a

commit_message:
Fixes Heat stack rollback on failed stack update

Stack rollback was disabled for stack create operation
but not for update

Change-Id: I6c032b2d7cf681e9c5aca086aa9fdde3da69a535
Closes-Bug: #1447718

commit_message:
Updating example config to work with example instructions

Since we can't expect that an example junk domain name will
resolve to a valid IP, I have removed the IP checking for now.
This will be moved to a documentation file soon.

commit_message:
Fixes k8s deployment without Replication Controller

UpdatePod execution plan was using field from Pod
definition that was present in v1beta1 API but is no
longer used in v1beta3

Change-Id: Ib57a0e5cc7104d5e1fa39b07644eab182a7fdf45
Closes-Bug: #1447594
(cherry picked from commit a680bf5899e006ff1e3ecf1ee3e3c7cce4a9bebb)

commit_message:
testr requires python's gdbm

Debian/Ubuntu have *helpfully* removed gdbm from the base python
package and put it into another package, which is not dragged in by
installing python. Testr doesn't function without this.

We should ensure this always gets installed.

Depends-On: If48a8444b02ee1e105bc1d9ce78a0489ea0c405b

Change-Id: I85a0ffe5ee384e055e78fd3164c27d42a86bc39d

commit_message:
add liberty to feature grid

This adds liberty to the feature grid based on our existing definition
of master. While not strictly needed now, this helps us roll forward
later.

commit_message:
Relax pysendfile requirement

This explicit pinning seems to pre-date global-requirements.
After ~2 years, pysendfile released 2.0.1 in May and it is starting
to trickle into distros.  This changes the pinning to a >=2.0.0.

Change-Id: Ie44914e261ec439ebeaf246948971af30d90a388

commit_message:
IBP: add retries to utils.execute

utils.execute should be able to retry command execution in case of
failure.

Controlled by additional 'attempts' key parameter, which is defaultly
set to 1.

Added 10 attempts to execute debootstrap/apt-get in build_utils.py.
That should protect from minor networking issues during downloading
of packages.

Partially implements: blueprint ibp-build-ubuntu-images

Change-Id: I5c547d613fcf8596f95b64623fe65150ae52c521

commit_message:
Fixed issues with upload tests results

We can see some exceptions during the upload of the Tempest tests
results to TestRail TMS. Looks like it is issue in TestRail API
and we need make our script more stable.

Change-Id: I01062d549cfdd276547e8b9cbd0c339bf7430162
Closes-Bug: #1447684

commit_message:
Mark saharaclient as being a universal wheel

Universal is used to identify pure-Python module(by bdist_wheel).
For these, it is sufficient to build a wheel with _any_ Python ABI
version and publish that to PyPI (by whatever means).

Change-Id: Ie177af75df2a3adfc0bdccd972e698d6318e29cb

upstream cleanup 05

commit_message:
Remove the lvm.conf filter during cleanup

This avoids us leaving the filter in the global lvm config. Without cleaning
this up, we can hit some failures to run stack.sh because devices are excluded
that we need to be able to see. This resets it to what it was before when
we do a cleanup.

Also, do this before we add the line, so we don't add multiple lines on
successive runs.

Closes-bug: #1437998
Change-Id: Idbf8a06b723f79ef16a7c175ee77a8c25f813244

commit_message:
Prevent DHCP resync from exhaust allocation_pools

This commit is to prevent dhcp resync-loop.

* Attribute "allocation_pools" can not specify [](empty list)
  when create/update subnet.

* Non-admin user can not delete dhcp-port.

Change-Id: I81ab3ae4808be4e366dbb268001ff28165d92224
Closes-Bug: #1447883
Related-Bug: #1443798

commit_message:
Collect static files before compressing them

It is good practise to call collectstatic before compress to make sure
all necessary static files are in place for compression and we don't
need to rely on some other process to collect static files before we
compress them.

Collectstatic has --noniput to not ask for any user input and
--clear to clear the existing files before trying to copy or link
the original file

Change-Id: I69c02acbf171d450708f5a90c3e63a36906bd47b

commit_message:
[install-guide] [yum] use createUser method to add ceilometer MongoDB user

This solves the following issue when using MongoDB version 2.6.x.

WARNING: The 'addUser' shell helper is DEPRECATED. Please use
'createUser' instead

Partially implements bp installguide-kilo.

Change-Id: I12bc31525283abb1e87f9448bcd9758a1399d3ad

commit_message:
Bump eventlet version to 0.17.3

eventlet 0.17.3 is the first release fully compatible with Python 3 when
eventlet is used with monkey-patching. It is required to port OpenStack
to Python 3. For example, Oslo Messaging test suite now pass with
eventlet 0.17.3. Currently, eventlet is disabled on Python 3 in Oslo
Messaging, which prevents many applications to be ported to Python 3.

More information on the project to port OpenStack to Python 3:
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Python3

Moreover, eventlet 0.17.2 includes a change to use a real logger
interface, so it makes possible to cleanup oslo.log (more information in
the bug #1440773).

Change-Id: I73e3056b5e8b9ce710c9c2d59fc5be8e03e28d2a
Partial-Bug: #1440773

UpdatePod execution plan was using field from Pod
definition that was present in v1beta1 API but is no
longer used in v1beta3

commit_message:
Correctly erase partitions containing a 'p' in their name

The previous glob would fail to match partitions names that
contained a 'p' in them. Partitions would not be erased when
using cciss or nvme devices. nvme devices also have a major
number of 259 (only in 2.6 kernels) which has been added to
STORAGE_CODES.

Change-Id: Ie40afcb29e31c85c2c6021187601d66321fe3a05
Related-bug: #1372547

commit_message:
Add support for non-text files

A first pass at adding support for non-text files.

This passes the content-type headers from swift to determine
how to serve up the file.

Change-Id: I905a31b68308c6a79ef863b94cebdaa14914b221

commit_message:
Change libvirt qulity warning function and comment

Got following error when start my compute node
Change some function name to align its function behavior
and update function comments about it.

File "/opt/stack/nova/nova/virt/libvirt/driver.py", line 507, in _do_quality_warnings
caps = self._host.get_capabilities()
File "/usr/local/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/libvirt.py", line 3153, in baselineCPU
if ret is None: raise libvirtError ('virConnectBaselineCPU() failed', conn=self)
libvirtError: XML error: Missing CPU model name

Change-Id: I0f72be3aaf9b122e3ed394fe82b9bdc272a1dc82

commit_message:
Fix translation compress for manuals

Not all manual repositories have a doc directory, adjust the paths.
Not all files should be compressed, we need to exclude in all
repositories - besides openstack-manuals - the glossary.

Change-Id: I358db42585699b05e893b66e1ac6d2927fb43ee3

[{'created': '2015-04-24 11:28:12.000000000', 'message': "Modify code with second set of collector settings

- In rollback/upgrade jobs when we revert 6.0 snapshot
and revert fails first time we set collector settings second time
but cluster nodes are offline and this situation isn't handled in
6.0 iso so we fails with index out of range error. As workaround
we will disable second set of collector settings for upgrade/rollback
tests

Change-Id: I746206767cf8cba354255ce9d4751ad271f1fa88
Closes-Bug: #1448012
"}]
commit_message:
Modify code with second set of collector settings

- In rollback/upgrade jobs when we revert 6.0 snapshot
and revert fails first time we set collector settings second time
but cluster nodes are offline and this situation isn't handled in
6.0 iso so we fails with index out of range error. As workaround
we will disable second set of collector settings for upgrade/rollback
tests

Change-Id: I746206767cf8cba354255ce9d4751ad271f1fa88
Closes-Bug: #1448012

commit_message:
Remove doc repositories from projects.txt

The documentation repositories maintained by the OpenStack
Documentation team are currently all in projects.txt. They
are not installed together OpenStack server projects.

While the syncing of requirements is nice, it's not essential that
Documentation repo are part of requirements. The Documentation
repos have additional unique dependencies that are not needed by
other projects.

Still, the Documentation team likes to ensure that their requirements
are not conflicting with global requirements to allow editors and
developers reuse environments.

As discussed with Documentation team, remove these repositories
now (see thread starting at
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-docs/2015-April/006362.html).

Change-Id: I807b061cf697dc79b26ffdfbe023c32600ddd346

commit_message:
Fix lp project to repo name conversion

python-keystoneclient-kerberos did not match the old pattern, so we were
trying to release from a repository that does not exist.

Change-Id: If9dcc4c4352b702e24149e0c31aa0b80a46fac80

commit_message:
Fix bug on --remove-older-then opt

Old backups was never removed because of the use
of "is not" rather "!=" in the source code.

Change-Id: I92d681d61f7eacd42410d8392f1dabeeba4e94e9
Closes: bug 1415865

commit_message:
Install optional-requirement packages for Rally docker image

Ensure python-mistralclient, python-muranoclient or other packages
are included in the Rally docker image, so user could do benchmarking
without extra work.

Change-Id: I246a961d02308aee87a77098bdd631cf1a3bbd0c
Closes-Bug: #1447648

commit_message:
Use fill method to simplify string wrapping

Avoid printing lines in a loop.
Just call a method that already does that.
Ref: https://pypi.python.org/pypi/parawrap

Change-Id: I462de3fa5eee05393229a0b33c99eeb0d5449eca

commit_message:
move to botocore clients technology

from https://botocore.readthedocs.org/en/latest/client_upgrades.html#client-upgrades

Version 0.104.0 emitted an ImminentRemovalWarning when using the old interface. This warning is now printed to stderr by default. A user can still turn off these warnings via the warnings module.
The develop branch on github will be updated to completely remove the old interface. At this point the client interface will be the only interface available when using the develop branch on github.
A 1.0 alpha version will be released. By default, pip will not pick up any alpha/beta releases.
A 1.0 beta version will be released.
A GA (1.0) version of botocore will be released.

Change-Id: Id6661e3e1e73de018e9b4de7612972654bb27422

Looks good to me, good change Jamie. One small question but nothing to prevent a +2, just curious.'}, {'account_id': 11861, 'date': '2015-04-21 12:24:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

(7 comments)

Overall great changes Jamie!  Maybe you should give the PowerPoint jockey thing a rest and come back to the light-side? :)

A few small questions/nits.  Also, confidence seems partially implemented, but we can't do anything with it now.  Is this the intention?  If so, call it out in the commit message so we don't forget that we have more work to do.  

At minimum I think we should define some confidence for each test (even if it's undefined).  We should also allow filters on it from the command line."}, {'account_id': 11716, 'date': '2015-04-21 12:59:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 15173, 'date': '2015-04-21 15:39:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Going to review more carefully now, but I had a lingering question from last night:
    return(bandit.HIGH, bandit.HIGH, 'Requests call with verify=False '

Also:
   return(bandit.LOW, bandit.HIGH, 'execute with run_as_root=True '

In plug-ins, we appear to be returning multiple severities (High, Medium, Low) for the same warning. Can explain a little more the reasoning behind this?

It's probably something obvious, but I didn't see it last night - maybe it will jump out at me in my next review :)"}, {'account_id': 11861, 'date': '2015-04-21 15:41:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Rob - one is severity and one is confidence, but I agree - we should do something to make this more explicit, otherwise the code looks confusing and test writers need to remember arbitrary order.  Maybe we can make these named parameters?'}, {'account_id': 11029, 'date': '2015-04-21 15:45:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Yeah, that was one of my main questions and the reason why I threw this up without getting all the tests updated to include confidence.

At the moment it's a 3-tuple - so each test should be returning (issue_severity, issue_confidence, issue_text).  I'll probably turn this into a named-tuple so they are labelled rather than relying on the not-immediately-obvious order.

Another option could be to use something like "return (bandit.SEVERITY.HIGH,  bandit.CONFIDENCE.HIGH, issue_text)" but I suspect the named-tuple would probably work better.'}, {'account_id': 11861, 'date': '2015-04-21 15:47:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Either approach seems good to me'}, {'account_id': 15173, 'date': '2015-04-21 15:54:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Ah ok, knew I was missing something! :)

I lean toward the named tuple idea because it is a bit more explicit. I could even see passing around dicts.'}, {'account_id': 11716, 'date': '2015-04-21 15:56:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Code-Review

+1 for named tuple, or dicts.'}, {'account_id': 11029, 'date': '2015-04-21 23:18:14.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-21 23:18:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-20 23:37:15.000000000', 'message': "Shift in result types & ranking scales

This commit completes work that was discussed during the OSSG mid-cycle.

Summarizing the major changes:
 - Result 'severity' has been moved from INFO/WARN/ERROR to a LOW/MEDIUM/HIGH
scale.  This, as previously, is intended to indicate the risk associated with
the issue being reported.
 - Result 'confidence' has been introduced, also with a LOW/MEDIUM/HIGH scale.
This is intended to allow a plugin writer to indicate their level of confidence
that the issue raised is truly a security problem.
 - A Bandit plugin may now return a result as a 2-tuple (issue_severity,
issue_text) or - optionally - a 3-tuple (issue_severity, issue_confidence,
issue_text).  Confidence will default to UNDEFINED if the plugin does not
return a value.

The commit includes updates across Bandit and plugins to utilize the new scales,
and updates to the associated functional test suite to maintain test coverage.

Additionally, this commit:
 - Modifies the labels on fields included in JSON and CSV output formats to
align with Bandit-internal terminology (likely a breaking change for consumers
of these formats).
 - Removes color output codes from Bandit configuration when not running in a
TTY, as they are not likely to be supported.
 - Adds a few more debug statements and includes a traceback when a plugin
fails, to aid in developing plugins.
 - Cleans up the command line arguments used with argparse a little.
 - Fixes PEP8 niggles.

Change-Id: Ia0f76b96d1e756ce605ce6b0b29eee8bd2830574

commit_message:
Shift in result types & ranking scales

This commit completes work that was discussed during the OSSG mid-cycle.

Summarizing the major changes:
 - Result 'severity' has been moved from INFO/WARN/ERROR to a LOW/MEDIUM/HIGH
scale.  This, as previously, is intended to indicate the risk associated with
the issue being reported.
 - Result 'confidence' has been introduced, also with a LOW/MEDIUM/HIGH scale.
This is intended to allow a plugin writer to indicate their level of confidence
that the issue raised is truly a security problem.
 - A Bandit plugin may now return a result as a 2-tuple (issue_severity,
issue_text) or - optionally - a 3-tuple (issue_severity, issue_confidence,
issue_text).  Confidence will default to UNDEFINED if the plugin does not
return a value.

The commit includes updates across Bandit and plugins to utilize the new scales,
and updates to the associated functional test suite to maintain test coverage.

Additionally, this commit:
 - Modifies the labels on fields included in JSON and CSV output formats to
align with Bandit-internal terminology (likely a breaking change for consumers
of these formats).
 - Removes color output codes from Bandit configuration when not running in a
TTY, as they are not likely to be supported.
 - Adds severity and confidence to the standard Bandit output for each issue.
 - Adds a few more debug statements and includes a traceback when a plugin
fails, to aid in developing plugins.
 - Cleans up the command line arguments used with argparse a little.
 - Fixes PEP8 niggles.

 It does not implement filtering by confidence, that will be a future todo.

Change-Id: Ia0f76b96d1e756ce605ce6b0b29eee8bd2830574

commit_message:
Update openid connect docs to include other distros

The author of the mod_auth_openidc apache plugin had created a pull
request to update the keystone install instructions for the plugin
  https://github.com/openstack/keystone/pull/5

commit_message:
Removing unused methods from utils.openstack.*

Following methods have not used in code and will be removed:
* sahara.utils.openstack.get_flavors
* sahara.utils.openstack.get_images
* sahara.utils.openstack.get_limits
* sahara.utils.openstack.get_user_keypair
* sahara.utils.openstack.get_volumes

Closes-bug: #1446176

Change-Id: Ie3d3280ebedf5211457e4fb6176320cecb1317a3

commit_message:
Adding bandit to test requirements

Bandit is used to perform security-focused static analysis for OpenStack
projects. Bandit can be found in stackforge at:
https://github.com/stackforge/bandit

Bandit will be used in upstream projects as part of their gate test
process. The initial goal is to integrate with Keystone.

Change-Id: I050dc1ed8978b28d76a25ecf9d602c9556883ed9

commit_message:
Fix 'openstack::logrotate' for 'host-upgrade.pp'

Since commit Ie7040ebcdc1a3329ebb7507807e5c27f0c87b484 we have reworked
logrotate configuration. Unfortunately, the 'limitsize' option was
removed but it still in use by 'host-upgrade.pp', so we are unable to do
master node upgrade right now. This commit is going to fix it by using new
options for 'openstack::logrotate' class.

Closes-Bug: #1447974

Change-Id: I6f4b58a9d5128d2ae1c90dae8119aae5f378d7cd
Signed-off-by: Igor Kalnitsky <igor@kalnitsky.org>

[{'created': '2015-04-23 03:49:02.000000000', 'message': "Restrict subnet create/update to avoid DHCP resync

As we know, IPs in subnet CIDR are used for
1) Broadcast port
2) Gateway port
3) DHCP port if enable_dhcp is True, or update to True
4) Others go into allocation_pools
Above 1) to 3) are created by default, which means if CIDR doesn't
have that much of IPs, subnet create/update will cause a DHCP resync.

This fix is to add some restricts to the issue:
A) When subnet create, if enable_dhcp is True, /31 and /32
   cidrs are forbidden for IPv4 subnets while /127 and /128 cidrs are
   forbidden for IPv6 subnets.
B) When subnet update, if enable_dhcp is changing to True and there are no
   more IPs in allocation_pools, the request should be denied.

Change-Id: I2e4a4d5841b9ad908f02b7d0795cba07596c023d
Co-authored-by: Andrew Boik <dboik@cisco.com>
Closes-Bug: #1443798
(cherry picked from commit 0c1f96ad5a6606c1205bd50ea944c3a383892cde)
"}]
commit_message:
Restrict subnet create/update to avoid DHCP resync

As we know, IPs in subnet CIDR are used for
1) Broadcast port
2) Gateway port
3) DHCP port if enable_dhcp is True, or update to True
4) Others go into allocation_pools
Above 1) to 3) are created by default, which means if CIDR doesn't
have that much of IPs, subnet create/update will cause a DHCP resync.

This fix is to add some restricts to the issue:
A) When subnet create, if enable_dhcp is True, /31 and /32
   cidrs are forbidden for IPv4 subnets while /127 and /128 cidrs are
   forbidden for IPv6 subnets.
B) When subnet update, if enable_dhcp is changing to True and there are no
   more IPs in allocation_pools, the request should be denied.

Change-Id: I2e4a4d5841b9ad908f02b7d0795cba07596c023d
Co-authored-by: Andrew Boik <dboik@cisco.com>
Closes-Bug: #1443798
(cherry picked from commit 0c1f96ad5a6606c1205bd50ea944c3a383892cde)

commit_message:
Add CloudFoundryDiego

This application installs a single VM instance of CloudFoundry Diego.
It will require a special image to be built. DIB elements are included.

Change-Id: I5c960294f8f85852db7e3321aed8d58f3f610977

commit_message:
Enable passing optional first-boot user-data

Currently all the OS::Nova::Server resource created don't pass any
user-data.  It's possible to pass user-data as well as using heat
SoftwareConfig/SoftwareDeployment resources, and this can be useful
when you have simple "first boot" tasks which are possible either via
cloud-init, or via simple run-once scripts.

This enables passing such data by implementing a new provider resource
OS::TripleO::NodeUserData, which defaults to passing an empty mime
archive (thus it's a no-op).  An example of non no-op usage is also
provided.

Change-Id: Id0caba69768630e3a10439ba1fc2547a609c0cfe

commit_message:
Add env storing for loaded environments

If env loaded from outer file, there is probability
that this outer file will be deleted. So, if template
uses some resource registry env, we need to store
this env in db.

Change-Id: I3efe6bf1d2c6f6dded8b91d59dc5b11c69f6272b
(cherry picked from commit d8fe35eee518036eab7f73aca28cf4d770ae7dc1)
Closes-bug: #1429141

commit_message:
Release Import of Translations from Transifex

Manual import of Translations from Transifex. This change also removes
all po files that are less than 66 per cent translated since such
partially translated files will not help users.

This updates also recreates all pot (translation source files) to
reflect the state of the repository.

This change needs to be done manually since the automatic import does
not handle the proposed branches and we need to sync with latest
translations.

Change-Id: I423ec8cbb5f21fbaa3f3889b8bc3c69f1654462a

commit_message:
Add env storing for loaded environments

If env loaded from outer file, there is probability
that this outer file will be deleted. So, if template
uses some resource with resource registry env, we need
to store this env in db.

Change-Id: Ib0c191db2dccac6d467a9961062424bc1f924c24
Closes-bug: #1429141

commit_message:
Fix rally show commands for existing users in deployment

This patch contains 3 fixes:

  1) Rally `show' commands catch properly exceptions from keystone
     and display human readble errors for Rally users.

  2) For each user his own resources should print be print.
     Before this patch table rows were summmarized (without flush)

  3) Print headers with information about which resource
     are displayed in table

Change-Id: Ibcc2051797bf61b3a4db3a9c781ecf750ec8f3ea
Closes-bug: #1437712

commit_message:
Rename dockerctl functions.sh to functions

Fixes issue on upgrade when old functions file
still exists, potentially confusing an admin
trying to make changes debugging later on.

Change-Id: I7b86265e194f921baff4d522f77dc889180ca5a2
blueprint package-fuel-components

commit_message:
Add repo check after cluster deployment

run 'yum -y clean all && yum check-update' or
    'apt-get clean all && apt-get update' exit code should be 0

Change-Id: Idbed0a334bfc22b07e78cce3835352c54d8d0c0c
Closes-bug: #1403090

commit_message:
Merge server groups tests between v2 and v2.1

Currently v2 and v2.1 have separate functional tests and their
corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges servers groups functional tests.
Also inheriting this tests class from ApiSampleTestBaseV3 instead of
ServersSampleBase as this does not use any ServersSampleBase class methods.

Change-Id: I687ce52a9844b830ee324105c4f49dec83534d9b

commit_message:
central.update_status should be transactional

Central's update status method issues a large number of SQL
queries for large zones with many recent updates, as a result
it's checking out many connections from our connection pool one
after another, contributing to bug 1445123. By wrapping the
call in a transaction, a single connection will be checked out
of the pool.

Partial-Bug: 1445123
Change-Id: Idfde7578e1a17a6a0585835fe614f787102563fa
(cherry picked from commit ac79df1567fb040067ed59d948e8a39fb90af177)
